00:01:23.550 --> 00:01:27.610
Our course has been very focused
on American, European

00:01:27.610 --> 00:01:28.250
type cultures.

00:01:28.250 --> 00:01:29.590
We talked a little about
different ones.

00:01:29.590 --> 00:01:31.110
I'll say a bit more
about that.

00:01:31.110 --> 00:01:33.790
And then, I'll talk about maybe
the most thought about

00:01:33.790 --> 00:01:38.270
disorder of social interaction,
autism.

00:01:38.270 --> 00:01:43.120
So enhancing our views
of ourselves, OK?

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:46.440
So most US college students rank
themselves as better than

00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:48.050
average students.

00:01:48.050 --> 00:01:49.960
So you can sit there in your
chair and you could go, no,

00:01:49.960 --> 00:01:50.970
I'm a pretty modest person.

00:01:50.970 --> 00:01:53.120
But really, I'm probably
better than the average

00:01:53.120 --> 00:01:54.040
student, right?

00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:57.160
And by the way, I'll tell you
faculty are the same.

00:01:57.160 --> 00:01:58.950
So a million high school
students rated their

00:01:58.950 --> 00:02:01.990
leadership ability
in one example.

00:02:01.990 --> 00:02:04.640
28% said they were average.

00:02:04.640 --> 00:02:09.580
70% rated themselves as above
average in leadership.

00:02:09.580 --> 00:02:12.700
You understand that only 50%
could be at most above

00:02:12.700 --> 00:02:14.210
average, or 49%.

00:02:14.210 --> 00:02:17.660
Only 2% said they were
below average.

00:02:17.660 --> 00:02:20.260
60% of the high school students
of these million said

00:02:20.260 --> 00:02:22.370
were in the top 10% in
their ability to

00:02:22.370 --> 00:02:23.620
get along with others.

00:02:26.810 --> 00:02:28.580
And by the way, just in case
you think it's picking on

00:02:28.580 --> 00:02:32.200
students, 94% of college
instructors rated themselves

00:02:32.200 --> 00:02:33.370
as better than average
teachers.

00:02:33.370 --> 00:02:37.640
So whether you're sitting there
or standing here, we all

00:02:37.640 --> 00:02:39.730
polish our image to ourselves.

00:02:39.730 --> 00:02:41.640
And we can decide, is
that a bad thing?

00:02:41.640 --> 00:02:43.930
Is that vanity or egoism?

00:02:43.930 --> 00:02:46.040
Or is that maybe a pretty
healthy way to

00:02:46.040 --> 00:02:48.220
bump through life?

00:02:48.220 --> 00:02:51.950
Is overrating yourself, short
of putting yourself in

00:02:51.950 --> 00:02:54.430
destructive situations, is that
a way to be happy and

00:02:54.430 --> 00:02:54.830
optimistic?

00:02:54.830 --> 00:02:57.830
Are we resilient?

00:02:57.830 --> 00:02:59.700
So people call this
self-serving

00:02:59.700 --> 00:03:01.140
attributional biases.

00:03:01.140 --> 00:03:02.540
And this will play out
a little bit like the

00:03:02.540 --> 00:03:03.970
fundamental attribution error.

00:03:03.970 --> 00:03:05.190
Let me remind you
of what that is.

00:03:05.190 --> 00:03:08.930
The fundamental attribution
error is when other people do

00:03:08.930 --> 00:03:12.130
things, it's their character,
and especially failings are

00:03:12.130 --> 00:03:14.240
because of failings of
their character.

00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:16.570
When we do things we're not
especially proud of or don't

00:03:16.570 --> 00:03:19.670
think are awesome, that's the
situation that made us do it.

00:03:19.670 --> 00:03:23.190
And we don't provide that same
understanding of the situation

00:03:23.190 --> 00:03:25.030
to understand the behaviors
of others.

00:03:25.030 --> 00:03:27.410
It's not intuitive to do so.

00:03:27.410 --> 00:03:31.650
So they did experiments where
the experimenter set up how

00:03:31.650 --> 00:03:32.950
well you would do on tests.

00:03:32.950 --> 00:03:35.625
They made a test super difficult
or easier, sensory

00:03:35.625 --> 00:03:38.110
or perceptual discrimination,
social sensitivity,

00:03:38.110 --> 00:03:39.080
competitive games.

00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:40.910
It's all set up by
the experimenter.

00:03:40.910 --> 00:03:43.820
They can make tests brutally
hard or pretty easy.

00:03:43.820 --> 00:03:46.800
They can make you do well
or make you do badly.

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:49.860
And when people did well and
they were asked to say why

00:03:49.860 --> 00:03:52.180
they thought they did well,
the usual description was,

00:03:52.180 --> 00:03:54.570
because I'm a particularly
social person.

00:03:54.570 --> 00:03:56.110
I'm very competitive.

00:03:56.110 --> 00:03:57.890
I'm extra good at sensory
perception.

00:03:57.890 --> 00:03:59.340
You pick it.

00:03:59.340 --> 00:04:03.210
When they did badly, that
was a tough test.

00:04:03.210 --> 00:04:05.070
It's rare for people to say,
that was an easy test!

00:04:05.070 --> 00:04:06.940
Who wouldn't do well?

00:04:06.940 --> 00:04:10.970
If you do well, people tend to
ascribe it to their character,

00:04:10.970 --> 00:04:12.900
and when they do badly,
the situation.

00:04:12.900 --> 00:04:14.150
even within ourselves.

00:04:16.910 --> 00:04:19.450
And it extends to families,
social and political groups,

00:04:19.450 --> 00:04:20.300
and sports teams.

00:04:20.300 --> 00:04:24.080
You may know I'm very proud and
happy to be a member of

00:04:24.080 --> 00:04:24.920
the MIT community.

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:27.800
Something happens bad
at MIT, I don't go,

00:04:27.800 --> 00:04:29.340
well, then, MIT stinks.

00:04:29.340 --> 00:04:32.250
I go, oh, there was a situation
that wasn't

00:04:32.250 --> 00:04:34.740
well-handled by an individual.

00:04:34.740 --> 00:04:36.180
Same thing you might
think about the

00:04:36.180 --> 00:04:37.570
country you belong to.

00:04:37.570 --> 00:04:39.290
We don't say, US did
something bad.

00:04:39.290 --> 00:04:41.040
Most of us don't go, well,
the US stinks.

00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:43.200
We go, that's situation
wasn't very good.

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:44.600
We've got to change things.

00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:44.950
Yeah?

00:04:44.950 --> 00:04:47.926
AUDIENCE: Do you think this is
saying more about how people

00:04:47.926 --> 00:04:49.744
explain things to others
or about what

00:04:49.744 --> 00:04:51.894
they actually believe?

00:04:51.894 --> 00:04:53.810
PROFESSOR: So the question was,
is it what they actually

00:04:53.810 --> 00:04:54.940
believe, or say to others?

00:04:54.940 --> 00:04:57.640
I think the evidence is it's
about what they say to

00:04:57.640 --> 00:05:00.640
themselves truly about how they

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:03.080
explain success or failure.

00:05:03.080 --> 00:05:05.080
OK?

00:05:05.080 --> 00:05:09.310
People are biased to attribute
their successes to their

00:05:09.310 --> 00:05:12.150
wonderful traits and their
failures to situations.

00:05:12.150 --> 00:05:14.780
But we talked earlier that that
can be a healthy thing.

00:05:14.780 --> 00:05:16.040
Because then, you
can bounce back.

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:17.840
You can say, well,
I did badly.

00:05:17.840 --> 00:05:19.190
But, hey, I'm a winner.

00:05:19.190 --> 00:05:20.490
And tomorrow morning,
I'll get up.

00:05:20.490 --> 00:05:22.200
And I'm back at bat, right?

00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:23.490
Instead of saying,
oh, I'm a loser.

00:05:23.490 --> 00:05:25.080
It's all just pointless.

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:28.330
So in what sense is it
good to have this?

00:05:28.330 --> 00:05:29.410
It's not a good thing
or a bad thing.

00:05:29.410 --> 00:05:32.670
It's probably a thing of
positive mental health but it

00:05:32.670 --> 00:05:36.790
can make us overlook
causes of things.

00:05:36.790 --> 00:05:41.030
So an example of that as we
construct social realities,

00:05:41.030 --> 00:05:42.730
and you may know this is
the original study.

00:05:42.730 --> 00:05:45.650
But there's a million since.

00:05:45.650 --> 00:05:47.650
An undefeated Princeton
team played Dartmouth

00:05:47.650 --> 00:05:48.780
in a football game.

00:05:48.780 --> 00:05:50.110
Princeton won.

00:05:50.110 --> 00:05:51.390
And then, they looked
at the newspaper

00:05:51.390 --> 00:05:52.330
accounts of the games--

00:05:52.330 --> 00:05:53.110
totally different.

00:05:53.110 --> 00:05:54.760
They showed the film
to students

00:05:54.760 --> 00:05:56.030
from the two campuses.

00:05:56.030 --> 00:05:58.760
And depending on which team
you were rooting for, you

00:05:58.760 --> 00:06:02.500
tended to view the other team
as dirty, not playing fair,

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:03.580
not doing the right thing.

00:06:03.580 --> 00:06:07.680
You don't have to be much of a
sports fan to notice things

00:06:07.680 --> 00:06:09.890
where the other team is not
doing the right thing and your

00:06:09.890 --> 00:06:12.440
team, when it doesn't do the
right thing, well, they were

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:13.260
under pressure.

00:06:13.260 --> 00:06:14.510
It was atypical.

00:06:17.130 --> 00:06:18.430
And that makes it, of
course, hard for

00:06:18.430 --> 00:06:19.220
people to get together.

00:06:19.220 --> 00:06:21.160
We don't too much worry about
Princeton/Dartmouth

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:22.710
tension in the world.

00:06:22.710 --> 00:06:26.110
But we do worry about tensions
in the Middle East between

00:06:26.110 --> 00:06:27.760
Palestinians and Israelis.

00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:30.940
When they see the same news
story, how do they interpret

00:06:30.940 --> 00:06:32.200
what happened in that
news story?

00:06:34.900 --> 00:06:38.700
So this question of if we have
illusions that we're better

00:06:38.700 --> 00:06:40.910
than we are a little bit, is
that a bad thing or is that a

00:06:40.910 --> 00:06:45.060
good thing was tested in an
ironic study by Alloy and

00:06:45.060 --> 00:06:47.490
Abramson looking at patients
with actual clinical

00:06:47.490 --> 00:06:48.730
depression.

00:06:48.730 --> 00:06:51.050
So they gave depressed and
non-depressed students tasks

00:06:51.050 --> 00:06:54.410
that varied in the degree of
contingency, that is how much

00:06:54.410 --> 00:06:56.820
the performance of the
participant actually

00:06:56.820 --> 00:06:57.790
influenced the outcome.

00:06:57.790 --> 00:06:59.630
They controlled that.

00:06:59.630 --> 00:07:01.500
And then, they asked people
afterwards to estimate the

00:07:01.500 --> 00:07:04.090
degree of contingency between
a button press and a green

00:07:04.090 --> 00:07:05.190
light going on.

00:07:05.190 --> 00:07:07.650
How much of it was you, and how
much of it seemed to be

00:07:07.650 --> 00:07:11.670
randomly done by the
experimenter?

00:07:11.670 --> 00:07:14.240
Depressed students in this
particular setting were more

00:07:14.240 --> 00:07:18.220
accurate in knowing when it
would depend on them.

00:07:18.220 --> 00:07:20.900
And non-depressed students
overestimated the contingency.

00:07:20.900 --> 00:07:23.890
They overestimated their
influence on the situation

00:07:23.890 --> 00:07:25.940
when the outcomes
were desired.

00:07:25.940 --> 00:07:28.430
Awesome, that's because
I'm awesome.

00:07:28.430 --> 00:07:30.800
And when things didn't go so
well, again, not really under

00:07:30.800 --> 00:07:31.300
their control.

00:07:31.300 --> 00:07:33.340
But they don't know that.

00:07:33.340 --> 00:07:34.290
It's the situation.

00:07:34.290 --> 00:07:36.880
Something was screwed up
with the experiment.

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:38.200
So they're more variable--

00:07:38.200 --> 00:07:40.030
they interpret the situation
much more,

00:07:40.030 --> 00:07:40.950
again, on these things.

00:07:40.950 --> 00:07:43.040
And you could say they're
less accurate.

00:07:43.040 --> 00:07:45.450
But you could also say that's
a way, again, to have

00:07:45.450 --> 00:07:47.970
confidence in yourself and
optimism about the future.

00:07:51.390 --> 00:07:54.020
Another way in which we believe
and justify our

00:07:54.020 --> 00:07:56.030
choices but a way in which we're
socially influenced is

00:07:56.030 --> 00:07:58.290
this, the phenomenon called
false consensus.

00:07:58.290 --> 00:08:01.410
People choose to engage in a
behavior that those people who

00:08:01.410 --> 00:08:04.140
do that believe that it's more
common and that more people do

00:08:04.140 --> 00:08:09.760
that, that when you do
something, the more you do it,

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:11.950
the more you think other
people do it, too.

00:08:11.950 --> 00:08:13.250
What's the big deal?

00:08:13.250 --> 00:08:14.650
You might know that feeling.

00:08:14.650 --> 00:08:17.500
So the original experiment on
the Stanford campus for this

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:20.220
phenomenon from Lee Ross was he
asked people carry around a

00:08:20.220 --> 00:08:23.350
sign on campus that said "Eat
at Joe's" for 30 minutes.

00:08:23.350 --> 00:08:25.140
Some people said
no, thank you.

00:08:25.140 --> 00:08:29.040
Some people said yes because
they were obedient.

00:08:29.040 --> 00:08:30.670
Compliance.

00:08:30.670 --> 00:08:32.539
Now, of the people who said yes,
I'll carry that sign for

00:08:32.539 --> 00:08:35.559
30 minutes, they thought the
majority of other people when

00:08:35.559 --> 00:08:39.409
asked to do so will do so.

00:08:39.409 --> 00:08:41.210
They thought, well, that's
the way most people are.

00:08:41.210 --> 00:08:42.730
And I'm going to behave
like most people.

00:08:42.730 --> 00:08:44.350
That's a false consensus.

00:08:44.350 --> 00:08:47.540
The people who said no, I won't
do it, they thought the

00:08:47.540 --> 00:08:49.280
majority would not do it.

00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:51.450
So part of their thinking about
deciding if they'll do

00:08:51.450 --> 00:08:55.640
something or not is their
estimate of whether people in

00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:58.250
general would do it.

00:08:58.250 --> 00:09:01.380
But what you can see happens
is that driven by whether

00:09:01.380 --> 00:09:03.140
they're going to do it or not.

00:09:03.140 --> 00:09:05.830
So for example, teenage smokers
estimate higher rates

00:09:05.830 --> 00:09:08.620
of smoking than nonsmokers.

00:09:08.620 --> 00:09:11.200
Domestically abusive men
estimate that about 28% of men

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:13.300
have violently thrown things
at their partner.

00:09:13.300 --> 00:09:16.460
Best estimates are
it's down to 12%.

00:09:16.460 --> 00:09:19.690
So we tend to overly believe
that other people will do the

00:09:19.690 --> 00:09:21.560
same behaviors that we do.

00:09:21.560 --> 00:09:23.155
And that's part of justifying
those behaviors.

00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:28.630
A demonstration of that was from
Phil Zimbardo, the social

00:09:28.630 --> 00:09:30.180
psychologist who did the
prison experiment.

00:09:30.180 --> 00:09:33.020
This has some of the same
flavor, not quite as dramatic.

00:09:33.020 --> 00:09:36.500
But he worked in New York before
he moved to Stanford.

00:09:36.500 --> 00:09:38.920
So he compared the Bronx
to Palo Alto.

00:09:38.920 --> 00:09:41.840
In 1980, the paper
was published.

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:46.050
And he left out cars, one in
upper middle class Palo Alto--

00:09:46.050 --> 00:09:49.380
very suburban area if you
haven't been there-- and one

00:09:49.380 --> 00:09:51.180
in a tough Bronx area.

00:09:51.180 --> 00:09:53.080
As you could imagine, you
leave a car out there by

00:09:53.080 --> 00:09:56.520
itself in the Bronx area without
a license plate and

00:09:56.520 --> 00:09:59.610
the hood was up, it was
stripped within a day.

00:09:59.610 --> 00:10:02.130
So you park the car, you push
up the hood, no license

00:10:02.130 --> 00:10:04.160
plate-- stripped within a day.

00:10:04.160 --> 00:10:08.000
In Palo Alto, it's untouched
for a week.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.530
So that's obviously to do with
the environment you're in.

00:10:11.530 --> 00:10:13.100
But here's the false
consensus.

00:10:13.100 --> 00:10:14.550
So then, they smash a window.

00:10:14.550 --> 00:10:16.170
And within an hour,
it's stripped.

00:10:16.170 --> 00:10:18.310
As soon as you smash the
window-- we talked about

00:10:18.310 --> 00:10:19.000
broken windows.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:19.950
Here it is literally.

00:10:19.950 --> 00:10:22.480
Soon as somebody says,
all rules are off.

00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:24.790
This car is smash, wrecked--

00:10:24.790 --> 00:10:26.370
that's the behavior
I can engage in.

00:10:29.800 --> 00:10:32.990
What you perceive as the
relevance, the environment of

00:10:32.990 --> 00:10:36.150
behaviors are appropriate,
hugely influences and

00:10:36.150 --> 00:10:38.510
justifies and drives
your own behavior.

00:10:41.910 --> 00:10:45.660
Now one of the tasks people have
to try to convince people

00:10:45.660 --> 00:10:48.090
to do public goods
in various ways--

00:10:48.090 --> 00:10:51.380
and this is an ad that when I
was younger was very famous.

00:10:51.380 --> 00:10:53.800
For you, it's so long ago
in history that you may

00:10:53.800 --> 00:10:54.530
not even know it.

00:10:54.530 --> 00:10:56.930
But it was one of the most
famous ones when the United

00:10:56.930 --> 00:10:59.670
states was first confronting
issues with environmental

00:10:59.670 --> 00:11:01.420
problems and pollution.

00:11:01.420 --> 00:11:03.140
You may not believe this, but
there was an era when there

00:11:03.140 --> 00:11:06.670
was fantastic pollution in the
air and the water and the land

00:11:06.670 --> 00:11:08.820
and nobody seemed to care about
it at all because land

00:11:08.820 --> 00:11:09.430
seemed endless.

00:11:09.430 --> 00:11:11.460
It wasn't even a thought.

00:11:11.460 --> 00:11:14.160
So Earth Day was
from the 1970s.

00:11:14.160 --> 00:11:17.920
That was the marking of a wider
consciousness of the

00:11:17.920 --> 00:11:20.970
consequence of ruining
the environment.

00:11:20.970 --> 00:11:23.270
And so in the very earliest
stages, when people weren't

00:11:23.270 --> 00:11:27.040
used almost any discussions of
that, there was this ad with a

00:11:27.040 --> 00:11:29.770
Native American with a tear
running down his face.

00:11:29.770 --> 00:11:31.020
And let me show you the ad.

00:11:39.020 --> 00:11:44.630
A very powerful ad at a time,
and one that I'll show you in

00:11:44.630 --> 00:11:46.890
a minute that social
psychologists believe was

00:11:46.890 --> 00:11:49.720
completely counterproductive
to the goal of reducing

00:11:49.720 --> 00:11:50.840
pollution--

00:11:50.840 --> 00:11:54.200
exactly the thing you don't
want to do because we just

00:11:54.200 --> 00:11:57.650
talked about false consensus and
about these environmental

00:11:57.650 --> 00:11:58.800
justifications.

00:11:58.800 --> 00:12:01.960
So I'll tell you, but
what does that mean?

00:12:01.960 --> 00:12:03.960
So if you see a lot of people
throwing garbage onto the

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:07.710
beach, onto the street, into
the river, what are you

00:12:07.710 --> 00:12:10.150
allowed to do?

00:12:10.150 --> 00:12:10.900
Pollute yourself.

00:12:10.900 --> 00:12:12.490
Hey, everybody else
is doing it.

00:12:12.490 --> 00:12:13.590
What's the big deal?

00:12:13.590 --> 00:12:15.430
That's the mode of
behavior, right?

00:12:15.430 --> 00:12:17.880
Broken window, steal the car.

00:12:17.880 --> 00:12:20.200
Litter everywhere, OK,
somebody is saying

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:20.880
it's not a good idea.

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:22.540
But the behavior that I see is

00:12:22.540 --> 00:12:24.070
littering, littering, littering.

00:12:24.070 --> 00:12:25.500
It's OK to litter.

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:27.550
So they literally showed
this in experiments.

00:12:27.550 --> 00:12:29.690
They took people into
areas, into parks.

00:12:29.690 --> 00:12:33.320
They surrounded them with
different amounts of trash.

00:12:33.320 --> 00:12:35.610
Here's the percentage of
people who litter.

00:12:35.610 --> 00:12:37.120
Here's how much trash
was around them.

00:12:37.120 --> 00:12:39.000
They went into parks and they
put a little trash and they

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.140
watched somebody come by.

00:12:41.140 --> 00:12:42.620
Still, some people
are littering.

00:12:42.620 --> 00:12:43.640
Maybe less would now.

00:12:43.640 --> 00:12:44.370
I don't know.

00:12:44.370 --> 00:12:47.430
But as soon as there was four
pieces or eight pieces of

00:12:47.430 --> 00:12:50.700
littering, then you more than
double the littering when

00:12:50.700 --> 00:12:52.330
there's zero.

00:12:52.330 --> 00:12:57.800
So the very example of showing
littering drives littering.

00:12:57.800 --> 00:12:59.890
You say, nobody's saying
it's a good thing.

00:12:59.890 --> 00:13:02.060
But hey, it's what everybody's
doing.

00:13:02.060 --> 00:13:02.810
And why do we litter?

00:13:02.810 --> 00:13:06.370
Because we're lazy and most of
us just don't want to bother

00:13:06.370 --> 00:13:09.300
to walk to the garbage can.

00:13:09.300 --> 00:13:13.730
So they did an experiment with
public service announcements

00:13:13.730 --> 00:13:16.310
where they said the important
thing is to see behavior, the

00:13:16.310 --> 00:13:18.230
behavior you want.

00:13:18.230 --> 00:13:21.080
Like in this case, it was
a recycling thing.

00:13:21.080 --> 00:13:25.460
And then, you show one example
of a person who doesn't do it.

00:13:25.460 --> 00:13:27.550
And you say, bad person!

00:13:27.550 --> 00:13:29.240
You don't say bad person, but
you send that message.

00:13:29.240 --> 00:13:30.700
You say, here's the
behavior we want.

00:13:30.700 --> 00:13:31.640
There's somebody doing that.

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:33.890
Uh-uh.

00:13:33.890 --> 00:13:36.000
And what they found
is that 25%--

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:37.260
this is truly in
the community--

00:13:37.260 --> 00:13:39.180
increase in recycling.

00:13:39.180 --> 00:13:42.270
So if you want to get people to
do things, showing them bad

00:13:42.270 --> 00:13:46.510
behavior unfortunately makes
them think that bad behavior

00:13:46.510 --> 00:13:49.440
is widespread and an acceptable
way to go.

00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:52.960
So you have to show them good
behavior and then give maybe

00:13:52.960 --> 00:13:55.030
one example of bad things
because you don't want to be

00:13:55.030 --> 00:13:56.040
labeled bad.

00:13:56.040 --> 00:13:58.860
But mostly, they have to see the
behavior you want, not the

00:13:58.860 --> 00:14:01.340
behavior you're trying
to discourage.

00:14:01.340 --> 00:14:05.970
So for a social psychologist,
exactly the opposite outcome

00:14:05.970 --> 00:14:08.850
of the intended ad.

00:14:08.850 --> 00:14:12.130
So this speaks to a gap
almost all of us have.

00:14:12.130 --> 00:14:14.980
Some of you may be more perfect
than I. Many of you

00:14:14.980 --> 00:14:17.080
may be more perfect than I.
But here's the gap we face

00:14:17.080 --> 00:14:19.140
every morning when we get up,
which is the difference

00:14:19.140 --> 00:14:20.920
between our attitudes
and our actions--

00:14:20.920 --> 00:14:23.120
the things we know are the way
we wish we were, the right

00:14:23.120 --> 00:14:25.580
thing to do, and the way in
which sometimes we don't

00:14:25.580 --> 00:14:28.760
always do the rightest thing
we know we could.

00:14:28.760 --> 00:14:32.260
So daffodil days, you may know,
occurs in many places

00:14:32.260 --> 00:14:34.510
including universities where you
buy a daffodil and there's

00:14:34.510 --> 00:14:36.910
a four day campus
event to benefit

00:14:36.910 --> 00:14:38.320
American Cancer Society.

00:14:38.320 --> 00:14:39.840
So it's a nice thing.

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:40.830
It's buying a flower.

00:14:40.830 --> 00:14:44.450
It's a good cause, fighting
cancer, very positive.

00:14:44.450 --> 00:14:49.040
So they did a study with
251 Cornell students.

00:14:49.040 --> 00:14:52.370
And they asked them, when
daffodil day comes up and you

00:14:52.370 --> 00:14:54.020
just spend a tiny bit of money--
it's a very small

00:14:54.020 --> 00:14:56.150
amount of money they
ask from students--

00:14:56.150 --> 00:14:58.000
will you buy at least
one flower?

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.190
And over 80% said,
yes, I will.

00:15:00.190 --> 00:15:02.870
For a cause like that, buying
a beautiful flower to fight

00:15:02.870 --> 00:15:05.530
cancer, I'll spend $1.

00:15:05.530 --> 00:15:07.010
How about the other students?

00:15:07.010 --> 00:15:08.510
Well, they're kind of lazy.

00:15:08.510 --> 00:15:09.590
And they have good intentions.

00:15:09.590 --> 00:15:11.610
But probably only about half
of them will do it.

00:15:11.610 --> 00:15:14.860
That's a little bit of
the self-affirmation.

00:15:14.860 --> 00:15:15.520
I'm a good person.

00:15:15.520 --> 00:15:17.710
Other people will be flawed.

00:15:17.710 --> 00:15:19.130
So how many people
actually buy it?

00:15:19.130 --> 00:15:20.590
43%.

00:15:20.590 --> 00:15:23.140
So what happened to this 40%?

00:15:23.140 --> 00:15:24.290
Well, it's a little bit
like the story.

00:15:24.290 --> 00:15:24.850
Things were busy.

00:15:24.850 --> 00:15:25.990
Things were happening.

00:15:25.990 --> 00:15:30.020
They weren't for cancer
and against flowers,

00:15:30.020 --> 00:15:31.200
just they got busy.

00:15:31.200 --> 00:15:31.840
There were exams.

00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:33.380
There was stuff going on.

00:15:36.500 --> 00:15:39.970
And how do we explain to
ourselves this gap between the

00:15:39.970 --> 00:15:43.480
attitudes we hold
and truly hold?

00:15:43.480 --> 00:15:45.220
We want to do good things and
be a good person, and the

00:15:45.220 --> 00:15:50.470
actions we do, which are often
a little bit below that?

00:15:50.470 --> 00:15:54.080
So this gap between our
attitudes and our actions has

00:15:54.080 --> 00:15:55.840
led to the phenomenon of
cognitive dissonance.

00:15:55.840 --> 00:15:58.460
You now hear this term
used widely.

00:15:58.460 --> 00:15:59.800
Originally, it had a pretty
narrow meaning.

00:15:59.800 --> 00:16:01.440
And I'm going to
be just talking

00:16:01.440 --> 00:16:02.105
about that narrow meaning.

00:16:02.105 --> 00:16:04.390
It's become a term that's
used much more widely.

00:16:04.390 --> 00:16:07.360
But here's the original
work from Festinger.

00:16:07.360 --> 00:16:10.180
He said that we have a problem
all the time that we have a

00:16:10.180 --> 00:16:13.820
gap between our attitudes and
our behaviors and that, as

00:16:13.820 --> 00:16:17.100
humans, we have to solve this
because we don't feel good

00:16:17.100 --> 00:16:19.510
about that gap.

00:16:19.510 --> 00:16:22.980
And so here's how we approached
showing how we

00:16:22.980 --> 00:16:24.220
solve that problem.

00:16:24.220 --> 00:16:26.510
Of course, the nice thing would
be just to do the right

00:16:26.510 --> 00:16:27.210
thing all the time.

00:16:27.210 --> 00:16:29.730
But that's not within, most
of us, somehow our grasp.

00:16:29.730 --> 00:16:30.580
OK

00:16:30.580 --> 00:16:31.930
So here's what he
had people do.

00:16:31.930 --> 00:16:35.290
He had people come in and do
a purposefully boring task.

00:16:35.290 --> 00:16:37.860
So they would pack and unpack
spools in a tray.

00:16:37.860 --> 00:16:40.000
Or they would turn tiny
little screws,

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:40.810
each of them a quarter.

00:16:40.810 --> 00:16:42.580
It was purposefully boring.

00:16:42.580 --> 00:16:44.700
You could tell it was boring,
and it was boring.

00:16:44.700 --> 00:16:47.430
This was the goal.

00:16:47.430 --> 00:16:50.100
And then, either nothing
would happen--

00:16:50.100 --> 00:16:51.180
that's one group--

00:16:51.180 --> 00:16:53.180
or you would get paid $1--

00:16:53.180 --> 00:16:54.290
not much money--

00:16:54.290 --> 00:16:55.740
or $20--

00:16:55.740 --> 00:16:57.400
considerably better--

00:16:57.400 --> 00:17:00.235
to lie and tell the next person
who's coming in that

00:17:00.235 --> 00:17:02.620
this was an interesting
and worthwhile task.

00:17:02.620 --> 00:17:04.310
So you imagine you go in there,
you do something that's

00:17:04.310 --> 00:17:05.220
really boring.

00:17:05.220 --> 00:17:06.109
Imagine you're in this group.

00:17:06.109 --> 00:17:07.880
They say, here, here's $1.

00:17:07.880 --> 00:17:10.890
Will you lie to the
next person?

00:17:10.890 --> 00:17:13.130
Or here's $20, will you lie to
the next person saying this

00:17:13.130 --> 00:17:14.520
was a pretty cool task?

00:17:14.520 --> 00:17:18.260
I can't believe how lucky you
are to have the next turn.

00:17:18.260 --> 00:17:20.525
And then they say, OK, now we
know you lied to that person.

00:17:20.525 --> 00:17:21.960
We asked you to do it.

00:17:21.960 --> 00:17:23.819
But really, really,
how was the task?

00:17:23.819 --> 00:17:26.089
Really, really, how
was the task?

00:17:26.089 --> 00:17:28.730
And here's the amazing
finding.

00:17:28.730 --> 00:17:31.440
If you don't lie, you say I
didn't like it very much at

00:17:31.440 --> 00:17:34.020
all, here's zero,
less than zero.

00:17:34.020 --> 00:17:40.800
If you are paid $1 to lie,
whoa, it really was good!

00:17:40.800 --> 00:17:45.210
If you're paid $20 to lie, you
pretty much agree it stinks.

00:17:45.210 --> 00:17:46.670
So how does that work?

00:17:46.670 --> 00:17:49.370
You have to see the irony
of this, right?

00:17:49.370 --> 00:17:52.120
So the interpretation is this.

00:17:52.120 --> 00:17:55.590
If somebody pays you $20 to make
a white lie-- you don't

00:17:55.590 --> 00:17:58.240
see this as a brutal lie, just
telling the next student that

00:17:58.240 --> 00:18:01.250
this is a pretty cool task--

00:18:01.250 --> 00:18:04.590
is $20 worth a white lie?

00:18:04.590 --> 00:18:05.780
You can live with that.

00:18:05.780 --> 00:18:08.050
You know why you did it.

00:18:08.050 --> 00:18:09.110
But $1?

00:18:09.110 --> 00:18:11.330
Would you sacrifice your
integrity for $1?

00:18:13.980 --> 00:18:14.920
You understand--

00:18:14.920 --> 00:18:16.540
$1?

00:18:16.540 --> 00:18:18.970
How cheap can you be?

00:18:18.970 --> 00:18:20.430
So their idea is this.

00:18:20.430 --> 00:18:22.910
But now they're asking them
really, really, really, really

00:18:22.910 --> 00:18:26.220
the way that people put together
their attitudes, like

00:18:26.220 --> 00:18:29.120
I lied for a mere dollar, is to
say, hey, it must have been

00:18:29.120 --> 00:18:31.200
more interesting than
I first thought.

00:18:31.200 --> 00:18:34.510
Come to think of it, it was
pretty interesting.

00:18:34.510 --> 00:18:34.785
Boom.

00:18:34.785 --> 00:18:36.000
Do you understand that?

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:39.770
So the effort to match up the
discrepancy between your

00:18:39.770 --> 00:18:43.000
attitudes and actions,
you solve--

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:44.390
you can't let them
go like this.

00:18:44.390 --> 00:18:45.350
You can explain this.

00:18:45.350 --> 00:18:46.830
I lied because I got
paid a bunch.

00:18:46.830 --> 00:18:48.280
But this, you can't explain.

00:18:48.280 --> 00:18:49.870
It's too hard to understand.

00:18:49.870 --> 00:18:52.760
And you really create a
rationalization that puts it

00:18:52.760 --> 00:18:53.390
all together.

00:18:53.390 --> 00:18:55.480
And you really, really report
now that this was

00:18:55.480 --> 00:18:56.730
a pretty good task.

00:18:59.870 --> 00:19:00.590
Here's another one.

00:19:00.590 --> 00:19:03.655
And this is not high
tech experiments.

00:19:03.655 --> 00:19:07.140
You can do amazing experiments
without zapping people.

00:19:07.140 --> 00:19:10.930
But by the time I tell you the
end of this one experiment--

00:19:10.930 --> 00:19:12.540
let's see if I have
one more on this.

00:19:12.540 --> 00:19:16.270
Nah, I'll mention it now
and then the next one.

00:19:16.270 --> 00:19:19.790
It pretty much ruins it whenever
anybody tells you how

00:19:19.790 --> 00:19:22.270
satisfied they are with almost
anything they've

00:19:22.270 --> 00:19:23.330
done in their life.

00:19:23.330 --> 00:19:24.580
This has ruined it for me.

00:19:24.580 --> 00:19:26.750
And I'll tell you why.

00:19:26.750 --> 00:19:28.640
Although I know that
you're better off

00:19:28.640 --> 00:19:30.700
polishing your happiness.

00:19:30.700 --> 00:19:32.530
So here's a simple experiment.

00:19:32.530 --> 00:19:34.880
This guy, Jack Brehm, had a
bunch of wedding gifts.

00:19:34.880 --> 00:19:36.580
And he took his wedding
gifts to the lab.

00:19:36.580 --> 00:19:37.980
It was not very high tech.

00:19:37.980 --> 00:19:40.970
And he had people rate how
much they wanted them.

00:19:40.970 --> 00:19:43.590
So he had stuff like a desk
lamp, a toaster, a stopwatch,

00:19:43.590 --> 00:19:46.100
a radio, a bunch of stuff
you got in the

00:19:46.100 --> 00:19:48.580
1950s as wedding gifts.

00:19:48.580 --> 00:19:51.390
People rated how much
did they like them.

00:19:51.390 --> 00:19:53.720
And then, he picked two that
were in the middle of the list

00:19:53.720 --> 00:19:56.160
and rated right next
to each other.

00:19:56.160 --> 00:19:58.840
And he said, will you pick
one of these two?

00:19:58.840 --> 00:20:00.090
You get to take it home.

00:20:02.760 --> 00:20:04.740
Will you pick one of these two
that you rated in the middle

00:20:04.740 --> 00:20:06.220
right next to each other?

00:20:06.220 --> 00:20:07.120
And you pick one.

00:20:07.120 --> 00:20:09.730
He says, OK, do one more thing
before you take it home.

00:20:09.730 --> 00:20:12.890
Tell me again your rating for
the different things here.

00:20:12.890 --> 00:20:16.120
And here's what they find,
that the items that

00:20:16.120 --> 00:20:18.580
you chose move up.

00:20:18.580 --> 00:20:19.600
You already have it.

00:20:19.600 --> 00:20:22.750
But let's say it was rated one
to 10, it was rated a five, it

00:20:22.750 --> 00:20:24.680
now becomes a two.

00:20:24.680 --> 00:20:28.430
Man, that stopwatch, that's
pretty awesome.

00:20:28.430 --> 00:20:30.330
I thought it was a five.

00:20:30.330 --> 00:20:32.040
But it's a two, maybe a one.

00:20:32.040 --> 00:20:34.880
I can't believe how lucky
I am that I picked that.

00:20:34.880 --> 00:20:36.410
And how about the one
you didn't pick?

00:20:36.410 --> 00:20:39.260
Say the toaster was number
six or number four.

00:20:39.260 --> 00:20:40.870
That moved to nine or 10.

00:20:40.870 --> 00:20:42.180
That toaster stinks.

00:20:42.180 --> 00:20:46.390
That would have been such a bad
choice to attend Harvard.

00:20:46.390 --> 00:20:47.850
It would have been a disaster.

00:20:47.850 --> 00:20:51.150
Thank goodness I picked MIT.

00:20:51.150 --> 00:20:53.190
So the idea is even something
like this-- and everything

00:20:53.190 --> 00:20:55.360
they do, college
choices, cars--

00:20:55.360 --> 00:20:58.700
any experiment you do, if you
have people rate after they

00:20:58.700 --> 00:21:01.230
made a decision about what
they're going to do, they

00:21:01.230 --> 00:21:04.930
always rate the thing they
picked as awesome on average

00:21:04.930 --> 00:21:07.380
and the thing they didn't pick
as much worse than they

00:21:07.380 --> 00:21:09.130
initially rated it.

00:21:09.130 --> 00:21:11.110
And again, you can say,
is that a way we can

00:21:11.110 --> 00:21:12.460
have a happy life?

00:21:12.460 --> 00:21:14.940
Would you want to be at MIT
every day going, if only I'd

00:21:14.940 --> 00:21:16.480
gone to Princeton!

00:21:16.480 --> 00:21:19.340
Would you want to get married
to somebody and say, if only

00:21:19.340 --> 00:21:22.870
I'd waited a little
bit longer.

00:21:22.870 --> 00:21:25.420
For your career, could you have
said, I went right to

00:21:25.420 --> 00:21:27.150
medical school or law school
or engineering.

00:21:27.150 --> 00:21:28.570
If only I waited longer!

00:21:28.570 --> 00:21:30.360
So you want to say no,
thank goodness

00:21:30.360 --> 00:21:31.160
I picked that college.

00:21:31.160 --> 00:21:32.510
Thank goodness I picked
that career.

00:21:32.510 --> 00:21:35.670
Thank goodness I picked that
spouse or partner because the

00:21:35.670 --> 00:21:38.150
other choices that were vaguely
in my head were awful.

00:21:38.150 --> 00:21:41.320
I don't know how I was even
thinking about them.

00:21:41.320 --> 00:21:43.560
So this has ruined it for me
every time anyone tells me how

00:21:43.560 --> 00:21:45.750
happy they are with a choice
they've made in their life

00:21:45.750 --> 00:21:47.790
because I look at this and go,
yeah, once you make that

00:21:47.790 --> 00:21:51.926
choice, you're going to rate it
as awesome no matter what.

00:21:51.926 --> 00:21:54.520
And a famous example is now many
of you are taking pretty

00:21:54.520 --> 00:21:55.960
tough courses.

00:21:55.960 --> 00:21:59.700
Years later when you come back
for alumni events-- and

00:21:59.700 --> 00:22:01.830
hopefully many of you will have
good feelings about MIT

00:22:01.830 --> 00:22:03.550
and come back and see
your classmates--

00:22:03.550 --> 00:22:06.870
and you'll get around and say,
oh, that course was so brutal.

00:22:06.870 --> 00:22:09.220
I know that won't
be this course.

00:22:09.220 --> 00:22:11.410
That course was so brutal
with the problem sets.

00:22:11.410 --> 00:22:14.960
But it made me a stronger
person, a better person.

00:22:14.960 --> 00:22:17.570
Thank goodness I did it.

00:22:17.570 --> 00:22:18.490
And maybe it does.

00:22:18.490 --> 00:22:21.100
But let me tell you
why you will think

00:22:21.100 --> 00:22:23.690
that in large numbers.

00:22:23.690 --> 00:22:26.880
So 1959, there's a little bit
of a sociological experiment

00:22:26.880 --> 00:22:29.820
in the sense you have to think
of people in 1959.

00:22:29.820 --> 00:22:32.260
And they were told to qualify
for a research study, some

00:22:32.260 --> 00:22:35.250
women were required to read
aloud a list of obscene words

00:22:35.250 --> 00:22:36.930
which are seen as extremely
embarrassing and

00:22:36.930 --> 00:22:38.340
inappropriate in 1959.

00:22:38.340 --> 00:22:40.560
Nowadays, it might be
the preferred mode.

00:22:40.560 --> 00:22:42.340
But in 1959, it was like,
I don't know.

00:22:42.340 --> 00:22:43.930
This is not right--

00:22:43.930 --> 00:22:44.930
or mild words.

00:22:44.930 --> 00:22:46.650
So that's the experimenter.

00:22:46.650 --> 00:22:49.785
Then, you got the privilege, if
you did this, to listen to

00:22:49.785 --> 00:22:53.290
a lecture on mating habits
of lower animals.

00:22:53.290 --> 00:22:56.910
But they made it the most
boring they could.

00:22:56.910 --> 00:22:58.680
This could go a couple different
ways, mating habits

00:22:58.680 --> 00:22:59.800
of lower animals.

00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:03.180
They made it super boring
on purpose.

00:23:03.180 --> 00:23:04.130
Lecture's over.

00:23:04.130 --> 00:23:07.320
And they ask the students
to rate the lecture, an

00:23:07.320 --> 00:23:09.870
intentionally super
boring lecture.

00:23:09.870 --> 00:23:11.980
And the women were either in the
group with the unpleasant

00:23:11.980 --> 00:23:15.090
experience of having to read
aloud uncomfortable word lists

00:23:15.090 --> 00:23:16.940
or just neutral words,
no big deal.

00:23:16.940 --> 00:23:19.680
Who rated the lecture better?

00:23:19.680 --> 00:23:24.800
The women who read the obscene
list of words because they

00:23:24.800 --> 00:23:26.630
were saying, well, why would
I do this if the

00:23:26.630 --> 00:23:29.000
lecture weren't terrific?

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:33.410
So the worse the experience
where you've had some sense of

00:23:33.410 --> 00:23:38.290
choice in it, the more people
will explain to themselves I

00:23:38.290 --> 00:23:40.630
took it for an extremely
good reason.

00:23:40.630 --> 00:23:43.030
I would not do a
painful thing.

00:23:43.030 --> 00:23:44.370
I'm not that incompetent.

00:23:44.370 --> 00:23:46.070
It must've been a
wise decision.

00:23:46.070 --> 00:23:48.980
And in fact, I should tell you
that if the examiner picks

00:23:48.980 --> 00:23:52.350
these items, you don't have
much of an effect.

00:23:52.350 --> 00:23:54.900
So if you rate items four and
five or five and six and the

00:23:54.900 --> 00:23:57.480
examiner gives you the
stopwatch, it doesn't change

00:23:57.480 --> 00:23:59.530
your ratings because you
didn't choose it.

00:23:59.530 --> 00:24:00.990
The examiner did.

00:24:00.990 --> 00:24:03.100
The stopwatch is a
mediocre gift?

00:24:03.100 --> 00:24:04.630
It's still a mediocre gift.

00:24:04.630 --> 00:24:08.500
But if you chose it, you have
to justify the choice.

00:24:08.500 --> 00:24:11.250
And there's 1,000 experiments
like this.

00:24:11.250 --> 00:24:13.490
Why did I do something
so painful?

00:24:13.490 --> 00:24:16.390
It must've been for a
very good reason.

00:24:16.390 --> 00:24:18.440
And then, you figure out what
that reason was, like the

00:24:18.440 --> 00:24:20.460
lecture was more awesome
than I thought.

00:24:20.460 --> 00:24:22.850
That physics course, that math
course, that computer science

00:24:22.850 --> 00:24:25.330
course just made me the
person I am today.

00:24:28.070 --> 00:24:30.320
We're going to switch gears
now, first impressions.

00:24:30.320 --> 00:24:32.850
So there's a book from Malcolm
Gladwell, Blink, which is

00:24:32.850 --> 00:24:34.900
really driven by this
phenomenon.

00:24:34.900 --> 00:24:37.590
The first impressions we take
of other people, how

00:24:37.590 --> 00:24:38.500
powerful are they?

00:24:38.500 --> 00:24:41.570
How valid are they?

00:24:41.570 --> 00:24:44.520
How accurate are they?

00:24:44.520 --> 00:24:47.440
So here's how we're going to
start the story, all the way

00:24:47.440 --> 00:24:48.510
back in 1966.

00:24:48.510 --> 00:24:50.410
They had students rate people's
personality on the

00:24:50.410 --> 00:24:52.980
first day of class before
they met each other.

00:24:52.980 --> 00:24:55.250
So if we had done this in this
course, imagine the first day

00:24:55.250 --> 00:24:58.470
of this course, imagine you're
not sitting with a friend and

00:24:58.470 --> 00:25:01.050
you're asked to people around
you on various personality

00:25:01.050 --> 00:25:02.110
dimensions.

00:25:02.110 --> 00:25:04.570
And the two that popped
out were sociable and

00:25:04.570 --> 00:25:05.610
responsibility.

00:25:05.610 --> 00:25:08.095
The people who said they were
sociable people tended to rate

00:25:08.095 --> 00:25:10.600
them as sociable just from
sitting next to them for a

00:25:10.600 --> 00:25:13.740
moment or as highly
responsible.

00:25:13.740 --> 00:25:17.490
So this is outgoingness and
personality psychology or

00:25:17.490 --> 00:25:18.340
extraversion.

00:25:18.340 --> 00:25:20.410
And this is something like
conscientiousness.

00:25:20.410 --> 00:25:22.710
Just talk to a person for
a couple of moments.

00:25:22.710 --> 00:25:27.600
You rate them pretty much like
they rate themselves.

00:25:27.600 --> 00:25:29.080
You don't know anything about
their background.

00:25:29.080 --> 00:25:30.490
You haven't had a
big interaction.

00:25:30.490 --> 00:25:32.770
Literally, it's moments next
to each in a course.

00:25:32.770 --> 00:25:36.680
Here's another one, 250 students
divided into groups

00:25:36.680 --> 00:25:39.810
of four who didn't know each
other and had not spoken.

00:25:39.810 --> 00:25:41.260
And they rated each other.

00:25:41.260 --> 00:25:43.480
And there was pretty good
correlations between moments

00:25:43.480 --> 00:25:48.230
of sitting together and how
sociable or extroverted people

00:25:48.230 --> 00:25:50.970
were, how responsible,
or conscientiousness.

00:25:50.970 --> 00:25:56.050
So a few moments with somebody
correlates pretty well your

00:25:56.050 --> 00:25:58.580
rating, on average, with how
they know themselves from a

00:25:58.580 --> 00:26:01.220
lifetime of personal
experience-- a few moments,

00:26:01.220 --> 00:26:02.470
pretty well.

00:26:02.470 --> 00:26:05.010
Now, we could say how well
do we rate ourselves?

00:26:05.010 --> 00:26:06.950
You could already pretty well
because it's pretty well

00:26:06.950 --> 00:26:08.410
adjusted with what other
people think.

00:26:08.410 --> 00:26:11.550
But here's another example where
they put strangers into

00:26:11.550 --> 00:26:17.040
groups, videotaped them, had
other people later on view the

00:26:17.040 --> 00:26:19.440
video tapes and rate things
like how extroverted they

00:26:19.440 --> 00:26:22.620
were, how much time did they
talk, how many arm movements.

00:26:22.620 --> 00:26:24.850
The impressions of the judges
watching the videotape

00:26:24.850 --> 00:26:28.240
correlated pretty well with
self-ratings and with ratings

00:26:28.240 --> 00:26:30.000
of other people who saw them
just for a few moments

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:30.600
personally.

00:26:30.600 --> 00:26:32.340
So all these things line up.

00:26:32.340 --> 00:26:34.870
Just from a few moments of
experience, you get a

00:26:34.870 --> 00:26:39.470
surprisingly strong consensus
about how outgoing somebody is

00:26:39.470 --> 00:26:43.630
and how conscientious or
responsible they are.

00:26:43.630 --> 00:26:45.770
And it lines up pretty much with
the person's own judgment

00:26:45.770 --> 00:26:48.370
about themselves that way.

00:26:48.370 --> 00:26:51.835
So this reached a huge moment
from Nalani Ambady who's now

00:26:51.835 --> 00:26:54.870
at Tufts having this famous
experiment, thin slices.

00:26:54.870 --> 00:26:56.800
And it's a fantastic
experiment.

00:26:56.800 --> 00:26:58.620
And if you ever teach,
it makes you nervous.

00:26:58.620 --> 00:27:00.730
Then, we'll discuss whether
it should or not.

00:27:00.730 --> 00:27:02.540
So at Harvard, here's
what she did.

00:27:02.540 --> 00:27:06.350
She took videotapes of 13
graduate teaching assistants.

00:27:06.350 --> 00:27:07.940
And they were horrible
video tapes.

00:27:07.940 --> 00:27:08.840
This is 1990.

00:27:08.840 --> 00:27:09.960
They were horrible videotape.

00:27:09.960 --> 00:27:11.280
I'm just going to tell you--

00:27:11.280 --> 00:27:13.780
you don't even see them around
very much because the quality,

00:27:13.780 --> 00:27:15.830
when you see them, you can't
believe people even

00:27:15.830 --> 00:27:18.500
saw things in them.

00:27:18.500 --> 00:27:24.320
And she got a random 10 second
clip, 30 seconds per teaching

00:27:24.320 --> 00:27:26.940
assistant, 30 seconds.

00:27:26.940 --> 00:27:28.620
She shows a silent
clip to students.

00:27:28.620 --> 00:27:29.605
There's no sound even.

00:27:29.605 --> 00:27:32.270
You're just seeing silently
some teaching assistant in

00:27:32.270 --> 00:27:34.750
front of students saying
something.

00:27:34.750 --> 00:27:37.840
And then, she has these students
rate from the silent

00:27:37.840 --> 00:27:40.520
film clip how accepting,
active, competent, or

00:27:40.520 --> 00:27:44.070
confident the teaching assistant
is who they've never

00:27:44.070 --> 00:27:45.450
met and, of course,
they don't know.

00:27:45.450 --> 00:27:46.370
And they don't know
what the teaching

00:27:46.370 --> 00:27:48.240
assistant's talking about.

00:27:48.240 --> 00:27:49.880
Here's the impressive thing.

00:27:49.880 --> 00:27:52.410
Then, they correlate the ratings
with the actual end of

00:27:52.410 --> 00:27:54.720
semester rating with students.

00:27:54.720 --> 00:27:57.250
They take the students who sat
through the entire course with

00:27:57.250 --> 00:28:00.200
a teaching assistant, that's
one set of values.

00:28:00.200 --> 00:28:03.870
They take the students
who see 30 seconds of

00:28:03.870 --> 00:28:07.030
silent, grainy videotape.

00:28:07.030 --> 00:28:09.510
And they say, how well do these
things do together?

00:28:09.510 --> 00:28:13.980
And they correlate 0.76,
which is really high.

00:28:13.980 --> 00:28:16.410
It's really high in our
field of research.

00:28:16.410 --> 00:28:21.480
That momentary, uninformed
impression correlates

00:28:21.480 --> 00:28:24.500
extremely high with what
students rate the teaching

00:28:24.500 --> 00:28:27.030
assistant after a full semester,
back and forth,

00:28:27.030 --> 00:28:30.030
seeing the teaching assistant
day in, day out, week in, week

00:28:30.030 --> 00:28:32.420
out for an entire semester and
all the interactions--

00:28:32.420 --> 00:28:35.000
super high correlation.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:37.230
And it stays if it's cut
from 30 seconds to

00:28:37.230 --> 00:28:39.410
15, or even six seconds.

00:28:39.410 --> 00:28:44.180
So this is a thin slice, a tiny
viewing of somebody, has

00:28:44.180 --> 00:28:45.620
this profound effect.

00:28:45.620 --> 00:28:50.160
So one impression you can have
from this is something like,

00:28:50.160 --> 00:28:53.030
gee, we form our first
impression--

00:28:53.030 --> 00:28:55.430
and I'll come back to that--
and once we form that first

00:28:55.430 --> 00:28:57.180
impression, that's it.

00:28:57.180 --> 00:29:00.980
The ship has sailed to
a remarkable degree.

00:29:00.980 --> 00:29:02.410
We can learn new things
about people.

00:29:02.410 --> 00:29:03.520
We can change our impressions.

00:29:03.520 --> 00:29:04.720
It's not that we can't.

00:29:04.720 --> 00:29:08.450
But to a remarkable degree,
we've set our final impression

00:29:08.450 --> 00:29:12.970
of that person within seconds
of interaction.

00:29:12.970 --> 00:29:14.610
Now, you could say, and of
course that's going to be

00:29:14.610 --> 00:29:17.280
fraught with every kind of
social prejudice you can

00:29:17.280 --> 00:29:19.010
imagine and complicating
prejudice you can imagine.

00:29:19.010 --> 00:29:19.750
Six seconds?

00:29:19.750 --> 00:29:22.210
Not a lot to sort through
intellectually.

00:29:22.210 --> 00:29:24.210
And it shows up in real life.

00:29:24.210 --> 00:29:26.310
For example, listen to 20
seconds of a physician

00:29:26.310 --> 00:29:28.230
speaking during a routine
office visit, they tape

00:29:28.230 --> 00:29:29.620
recorded them.

00:29:29.620 --> 00:29:32.140
Above chance prediction of who
was sued for malpractice or

00:29:32.140 --> 00:29:35.320
not because if you like a
doctor, you tend to forgive an

00:29:35.320 --> 00:29:36.740
error as a human error.

00:29:36.740 --> 00:29:39.210
If you don't like a doctor,
you're going to sue that

00:29:39.210 --> 00:29:41.970
person because you're
pretty mad at them.

00:29:41.970 --> 00:29:43.400
So do you give them
the benefit of the

00:29:43.400 --> 00:29:44.600
doubt they made a mistake?

00:29:44.600 --> 00:29:47.050
Or do you think they ought to
be sued and punished for the

00:29:47.050 --> 00:29:48.790
bad thing they did to you?

00:29:48.790 --> 00:29:51.690
Depends how much you like the
person to start with.

00:29:51.690 --> 00:29:53.600
Now, so one thing could
be that we go by first

00:29:53.600 --> 00:29:54.500
impressions.

00:29:54.500 --> 00:29:56.300
What's the other possibility
you could imagine?

00:30:00.510 --> 00:30:02.340
The pessimistic view
of this is--

00:30:02.340 --> 00:30:03.820
and it's somewhere, I think,
really in the middle, it's

00:30:03.820 --> 00:30:04.540
just human nature.

00:30:04.540 --> 00:30:07.590
The pessimistic view
is six seconds?

00:30:07.590 --> 00:30:09.650
When we talk about this, the
teaching assistants and I as

00:30:09.650 --> 00:30:11.860
we'd be in the course go, oh,
please, have that first six

00:30:11.860 --> 00:30:14.830
seconds go OK because that's
going to be 3/4 of your

00:30:14.830 --> 00:30:15.700
teaching evaluations--

00:30:15.700 --> 00:30:17.040
which are due Monday
by 9:00 AM.

00:30:19.810 --> 00:30:22.790
So please fill those out, by
the way, this reminds me.

00:30:22.790 --> 00:30:24.480
The first six seconds, and
that's pretty much it.

00:30:24.480 --> 00:30:26.240
And everything we do for the
rest of the semester,

00:30:26.240 --> 00:30:28.170
everything we do for the rest of
the semester, is only going

00:30:28.170 --> 00:30:30.180
to be about a quarter
of your rating.

00:30:30.180 --> 00:30:32.200
That's hard to believe, right?

00:30:32.200 --> 00:30:35.490
So one thing is it's all a big
confusion and humans just--

00:30:35.490 --> 00:30:38.310
what's the other possibility
that's a little bit more

00:30:38.310 --> 00:30:41.900
optimistic and maybe accurate?

00:30:41.900 --> 00:30:44.100
We know what we like.

00:30:44.100 --> 00:30:46.620
We know what we like, OK?

00:30:46.620 --> 00:30:49.850
And amazingly, we can tell
within seconds under many

00:30:49.850 --> 00:30:52.240
circumstance whether there's
something about a person that

00:30:52.240 --> 00:30:54.550
we like or don't.

00:30:54.550 --> 00:30:55.890
It's not that the six
seconds are just

00:30:55.890 --> 00:30:58.210
superficial in a dumb way.

00:30:58.210 --> 00:31:01.690
It's that we detect things about
that person that truly

00:31:01.690 --> 00:31:04.170
are something about
who they are.

00:31:04.170 --> 00:31:06.130
And that tends to carry all
the way through our human

00:31:06.130 --> 00:31:08.630
interactions with them.

00:31:08.630 --> 00:31:13.010
So I think it's somewhere
in that range.

00:31:13.010 --> 00:31:13.970
And does it matter?

00:31:13.970 --> 00:31:15.890
Is it all just about popularity
contests?

00:31:15.890 --> 00:31:17.140
Or does it affect
other things?

00:31:17.140 --> 00:31:20.980
So just staying within the realm
of teaching, they asked

00:31:20.980 --> 00:31:26.670
if you perceive somebody as more
likable or conscientious,

00:31:26.670 --> 00:31:28.180
are they more effective
teachers?

00:31:28.180 --> 00:31:30.220
Does it circle around
like that?

00:31:30.220 --> 00:31:32.220
So they have five students
in random groups.

00:31:32.220 --> 00:31:34.600
One was randomly chosen
to be a teacher.

00:31:34.600 --> 00:31:36.630
And these teachers prepared
brief math lessons.

00:31:36.630 --> 00:31:37.980
The students then
took the test.

00:31:37.980 --> 00:31:41.155
And strangers rated 10 seconds
of videos of these teachers.

00:31:41.155 --> 00:31:42.650
So people prepared
math lessons.

00:31:42.650 --> 00:31:45.250
Some better, some worse,
as you would imagine.

00:31:45.250 --> 00:31:49.020
The higher these were rated in
these 10 second thin slice

00:31:49.020 --> 00:31:52.330
videos by an external group, the
better the test scores of

00:31:52.330 --> 00:31:55.520
the actual participants because
something about

00:31:55.520 --> 00:31:56.950
effective teaching is something

00:31:56.950 --> 00:31:58.320
about engaging students.

00:31:58.320 --> 00:32:01.540
Something about engaging
students is something about

00:32:01.540 --> 00:32:05.130
being outgoing or something like
that to a certain degree.

00:32:05.130 --> 00:32:07.630
So it's not just arbitrary.

00:32:07.630 --> 00:32:11.760
There's something real in
the world that happens.

00:32:11.760 --> 00:32:14.390
And here's a few examples
where people have messed

00:32:14.390 --> 00:32:17.140
around with that because there's
two things that happen

00:32:17.140 --> 00:32:17.670
that are tricky.

00:32:17.670 --> 00:32:21.310
One is we know what we like
and we detect it amazingly

00:32:21.310 --> 00:32:24.130
quickly in people on average
to a large extent--

00:32:24.130 --> 00:32:27.920
certainly with error, but to a
surprisingly vigorous extent.

00:32:27.920 --> 00:32:30.240
On the other hand-- and we'll
come back to this--

00:32:30.240 --> 00:32:33.390
once we have that first
impression, as faulty as it

00:32:33.390 --> 00:32:37.490
may be in part, we keep
interpreting things in terms

00:32:37.490 --> 00:32:39.550
of that first impression.

00:32:39.550 --> 00:32:42.800
We give you the benefit of the
doubt or we don't behavior

00:32:42.800 --> 00:32:43.390
after behavior.

00:32:43.390 --> 00:32:46.530
So this was a study that
was done at MIT.

00:32:46.530 --> 00:32:49.120
Now, you're going to get
some prior information.

00:32:49.120 --> 00:32:51.290
Half the students were told,
the lecture you're about to

00:32:51.290 --> 00:32:54.690
have, people know him and
consider him to be--

00:32:54.690 --> 00:32:55.480
and then here's the--

00:32:55.480 --> 00:32:57.690
you're in the group that's told
he's a very warm person,

00:32:57.690 --> 00:32:59.430
industrious, critical,
practical, and determined.

00:32:59.430 --> 00:33:03.210
Or half of you would get the
information that he's a cold

00:33:03.210 --> 00:33:06.920
person, industrious, critical,
practical, and determined.

00:33:06.920 --> 00:33:09.860
So you just got an impression,
a warm or cold person.

00:33:09.860 --> 00:33:11.830
You haven't even seen
the person.

00:33:11.830 --> 00:33:14.450
Person gets up and leads
a 20 minute discussion.

00:33:14.450 --> 00:33:16.560
Then, you're asked to fill
out evaluations.

00:33:16.560 --> 00:33:19.230
Let me just pick the example
of the warm person.

00:33:19.230 --> 00:33:21.450
The lecturer is rated
as better.

00:33:21.450 --> 00:33:23.470
But here's the really
cool part--

00:33:23.470 --> 00:33:27.380
students took more part
in discussion.

00:33:27.380 --> 00:33:28.450
And do you see how
that probably

00:33:28.450 --> 00:33:30.530
made the section better?

00:33:30.530 --> 00:33:32.320
Because if you think this
is a nice person, so

00:33:32.320 --> 00:33:33.300
I can make a comment.

00:33:33.300 --> 00:33:35.740
I won't get my head bit off that
I didn't do the reading

00:33:35.740 --> 00:33:38.320
or whatever, it makes
a section better.

00:33:38.320 --> 00:33:41.360
They think it's better, but they
make it better because

00:33:41.360 --> 00:33:43.070
they think the person's a person
they want to interact

00:33:43.070 --> 00:33:45.580
with simply because they were
told on a piece of paper the

00:33:45.580 --> 00:33:46.650
person's warm or cold.

00:33:46.650 --> 00:33:49.470
The person's identical
time after time.

00:33:49.470 --> 00:33:52.470
So the first impression,
we know what we like.

00:33:52.470 --> 00:33:54.500
It's surprisingly accurate
in certain ways.

00:33:54.500 --> 00:33:56.960
But it's hard to change because
new information is

00:33:56.960 --> 00:33:58.830
interpreted to be consistent
with already formed

00:33:58.830 --> 00:34:00.080
impressions.

00:34:00.080 --> 00:34:02.540
So first impressions are
unbelievably interesting

00:34:02.540 --> 00:34:05.660
because they seem to be so
powerful in how we choose who

00:34:05.660 --> 00:34:08.679
we like and don't like, who we
hire and don't hire, who we

00:34:08.679 --> 00:34:11.230
work with and don't work with,
who we have relationships and

00:34:11.230 --> 00:34:12.570
don't have relationships with.

00:34:12.570 --> 00:34:14.389
And they're based on incredibly
little bits of

00:34:14.389 --> 00:34:16.469
information which are
tantalizingly

00:34:16.469 --> 00:34:18.030
accurate in one sense.

00:34:18.030 --> 00:34:23.540
But once we have them, it's
hard to override them.

00:34:23.540 --> 00:34:27.270
So here's a famous experiment
on the self-fulfilling

00:34:27.270 --> 00:34:29.639
prophecy that happens from this
first impression that you

00:34:29.639 --> 00:34:31.900
create, or the experimenter
creates.

00:34:31.900 --> 00:34:34.770
So a famous study where
elementary school children

00:34:34.770 --> 00:34:36.350
gave a test to students.

00:34:36.350 --> 00:34:38.980
The researchers said, we're
going to tell you whether this

00:34:38.980 --> 00:34:41.870
student is going to have-- we
believe, based on our research

00:34:41.870 --> 00:34:43.179
at Harvard--

00:34:43.179 --> 00:34:45.590
a good or bad year.

00:34:45.590 --> 00:34:47.870
So you're an elementary
school teacher.

00:34:47.870 --> 00:34:48.850
And then, you wonder.

00:34:48.850 --> 00:34:49.840
But they say, oh,
no, we've done

00:34:49.840 --> 00:34:51.239
fantastic research at Harvard.

00:34:51.239 --> 00:34:52.870
We're the top scholars
in the field.

00:34:52.870 --> 00:34:54.920
And we've developed an algorithm
that tells you is

00:34:54.920 --> 00:34:57.420
this student going to have a
good year or a bad year?

00:34:57.420 --> 00:34:59.950
The teacher gets that
information back.

00:34:59.950 --> 00:35:03.190
And at the end of the year,
better scores for those kids

00:35:03.190 --> 00:35:07.590
randomly described as going to
have a good year, worse scores

00:35:07.590 --> 00:35:09.210
for those kids randomly
described as they're going to

00:35:09.210 --> 00:35:11.580
have a bad year.

00:35:11.580 --> 00:35:13.210
Now, they didn't tape
everything.

00:35:13.210 --> 00:35:15.010
Nowadays, we could
tape everything.

00:35:15.010 --> 00:35:16.550
But what do you guess
that happened?

00:35:16.550 --> 00:35:18.520
And this might remind you of an
experiment we talked about

00:35:18.520 --> 00:35:20.110
with rats, except now
it's children in

00:35:20.110 --> 00:35:21.360
school in real life.

00:35:24.340 --> 00:35:26.690
First impression, right?

00:35:26.690 --> 00:35:29.130
When you've been told by
a crack team of Harvard

00:35:29.130 --> 00:35:31.750
researchers that some kid is
going to be slumpy, when they

00:35:31.750 --> 00:35:34.690
make a mistake answering a math
question, you go, oh, why

00:35:34.690 --> 00:35:38.000
am I spending my time
on this student?

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:41.420
It's not worth my
teaching skills.

00:35:41.420 --> 00:35:43.280
Somebody else gives
a good answer or

00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:44.070
makes the same mistake.

00:35:44.070 --> 00:35:46.220
And you go, oh, we're going
to help this student.

00:35:46.220 --> 00:35:48.660
They're one inch away from
being perfect on their

00:35:48.660 --> 00:35:50.370
multiplication table.

00:35:50.370 --> 00:35:51.780
So the very same behavior gets

00:35:51.780 --> 00:35:53.330
interpreted as pretty different.

00:35:53.330 --> 00:35:56.260
Or maybe just remember when
they gave the right answer

00:35:56.260 --> 00:35:58.910
really well because you think,
that's that student that got

00:35:58.910 --> 00:35:59.890
three and four correctly.

00:35:59.890 --> 00:36:02.180
But once you that first
impression, all of the other

00:36:02.180 --> 00:36:04.035
behaviors start to be
interpreted in that context.

00:36:08.370 --> 00:36:12.210
So one category of things mixed
into first impressions

00:36:12.210 --> 00:36:15.330
that have been studied a lot
is consensus physical

00:36:15.330 --> 00:36:15.900
attractiveness.

00:36:15.900 --> 00:36:18.470
Of course, different people
think differently about

00:36:18.470 --> 00:36:19.400
physical attractiveness.

00:36:19.400 --> 00:36:21.070
But in the cultures we live
in, there tends to be

00:36:21.070 --> 00:36:24.830
consensus about the average
movie star or beauty

00:36:24.830 --> 00:36:28.360
contestant or whatever
is the era's way of a

00:36:28.360 --> 00:36:29.670
people being seen.

00:36:29.670 --> 00:36:32.045
So people have shown again and
again, this will not surprise

00:36:32.045 --> 00:36:34.070
you, that physically attractive
people are judged

00:36:34.070 --> 00:36:38.180
as more intelligent, competent,
social, and moral.

00:36:38.180 --> 00:36:41.470
Now, why is that?

00:36:41.470 --> 00:36:42.430
So here's an example.

00:36:42.430 --> 00:36:44.160
Fifth grade teachers were
given report cards and

00:36:44.160 --> 00:36:46.720
photographs of children
they did not know.

00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:49.380
The photographs were picked to
be of children who looked, by

00:36:49.380 --> 00:36:52.060
consensus, to be attractive or,
by consensus, to be not so

00:36:52.060 --> 00:36:53.650
attractive.

00:36:53.650 --> 00:36:55.970
And they're asked to rate, based
on the report cards and

00:36:55.970 --> 00:36:57.490
the photos, the intelligence
and

00:36:57.490 --> 00:36:58.990
achievement of the children.

00:36:58.990 --> 00:37:01.470
The attractive children ended
up on average rated as

00:37:01.470 --> 00:37:03.940
brighter and more successful
than the unattractive children

00:37:03.940 --> 00:37:05.980
with identical report cards.

00:37:05.980 --> 00:37:07.640
They're sitting there with
all the information.

00:37:07.640 --> 00:37:09.360
They're making these
vague judgments.

00:37:09.360 --> 00:37:11.280
And the attractiveness element,
even from the photo,

00:37:11.280 --> 00:37:14.300
is coming in to the teachers.

00:37:14.300 --> 00:37:18.420
A child's misbehavior is
attributed to environmental

00:37:18.420 --> 00:37:22.200
circumstances if it's a more
attractive child and to

00:37:22.200 --> 00:37:24.030
personality if it's a less
attractive child.

00:37:24.030 --> 00:37:26.900
Again, this trade off between
character and situation.

00:37:26.900 --> 00:37:28.930
The attractive child
did something bad.

00:37:28.930 --> 00:37:31.160
Oh, there must have been
something in this situation

00:37:31.160 --> 00:37:32.760
that wasn't well done.

00:37:32.760 --> 00:37:35.060
The less attractive child
does poorly, and you

00:37:35.060 --> 00:37:38.010
go, oh, that loser!

00:37:38.010 --> 00:37:38.770
Right?

00:37:38.770 --> 00:37:41.070
I'm overstating, but you see
how what's happening is

00:37:41.070 --> 00:37:42.170
basically-- well, we'll
talk about it in a

00:37:42.170 --> 00:37:43.460
moment, court cases.

00:37:43.460 --> 00:37:45.370
People have done studies
on court cases.

00:37:45.370 --> 00:37:47.550
Shorter sentence for more
attractive people, longer

00:37:47.550 --> 00:37:50.290
sentence for less attractive
people for what seem to be

00:37:50.290 --> 00:37:53.650
comparable crimes.

00:37:53.650 --> 00:37:56.630
So people call this a halo
effect, that you take one

00:37:56.630 --> 00:37:58.720
positive dimension
of a person--

00:37:58.720 --> 00:37:59.470
it could be any.

00:37:59.470 --> 00:38:03.200
Physical attractiveness is one
of the easiest ones to

00:38:03.200 --> 00:38:04.800
experimentally study.

00:38:04.800 --> 00:38:07.735
And once you say one thing is
positive, you tend to rate

00:38:07.735 --> 00:38:08.740
other things as positive.

00:38:08.740 --> 00:38:10.410
It's just human nature.

00:38:10.410 --> 00:38:12.470
She's likable, so she's
intelligent.

00:38:12.470 --> 00:38:15.610
He's attractive,
so he's smart.

00:38:15.610 --> 00:38:17.450
People do this.

00:38:17.450 --> 00:38:20.020
You could argue it's not a wise
thing to, an accurate

00:38:20.020 --> 00:38:21.725
thing to do, definitely not.

00:38:21.725 --> 00:38:23.060
But people tend to do it.

00:38:23.060 --> 00:38:24.450
They'd leak categories.

00:38:24.450 --> 00:38:26.720
Once they have positive
information in one dimension,

00:38:26.720 --> 00:38:28.230
they start to make positive
assumptions in other

00:38:28.230 --> 00:38:30.180
dimensions.

00:38:30.180 --> 00:38:31.520
And there's all kinds
of examples.

00:38:31.520 --> 00:38:34.220
There's 1,000 of these studies
because they're easy to do and

00:38:34.220 --> 00:38:35.670
they're popular to do.

00:38:35.670 --> 00:38:39.110
But anyway, so here's one
example where they were told

00:38:39.110 --> 00:38:43.880
that the goal was to study
teacher evaluations.

00:38:43.880 --> 00:38:47.600
And what they really saw were
videos of a lecture of a

00:38:47.600 --> 00:38:49.150
person with a strong
Belgian accent.

00:38:49.150 --> 00:38:52.760
This accent matters for this.

00:38:52.760 --> 00:38:55.280
And they saw the videos of a
person answering questions in

00:38:55.280 --> 00:38:57.820
a warm and friendly manner or
a cold and distant manner.

00:38:57.820 --> 00:38:58.810
This was done on purpose.

00:38:58.810 --> 00:39:03.510
Now, in these two videos, they
rated the person in the warm--

00:39:03.510 --> 00:39:06.940
the same person, in one set of
videos they were warm in

00:39:06.940 --> 00:39:08.740
answering and the other, they
were cold and distance.

00:39:08.740 --> 00:39:10.910
So same person, but
in two videos.

00:39:10.910 --> 00:39:13.740
Now, they're asked to rate other
dimensions besides the

00:39:13.740 --> 00:39:15.630
warmness of the person.

00:39:15.630 --> 00:39:17.785
They said, oh, the person who
is warm was more attractive.

00:39:17.785 --> 00:39:18.780
Now, it's run the other way.

00:39:18.780 --> 00:39:20.540
The nicer person was
more attractive,

00:39:20.540 --> 00:39:22.450
more likable, and--

00:39:22.450 --> 00:39:23.660
kind of impressively--

00:39:23.660 --> 00:39:26.760
had less of an accent.

00:39:26.760 --> 00:39:27.070
You understand?

00:39:27.070 --> 00:39:30.250
Because accents, the challenge
of accents is sometimes

00:39:30.250 --> 00:39:32.010
they're a little hard
to understand.

00:39:32.010 --> 00:39:33.750
So you say, how hard was
it to understand?

00:39:33.750 --> 00:39:35.820
Oh, that nice person?

00:39:35.820 --> 00:39:39.530
Handsome and pretty easy
to understand.

00:39:39.530 --> 00:39:44.610
Less nice person, on purpose
acting out, not so attractive.

00:39:44.610 --> 00:39:48.920
And who could understand that
thick Belgian accent?

00:39:48.920 --> 00:39:52.020
They pick the accent because
they say that's ridiculous.

00:39:52.020 --> 00:39:54.120
It's ridiculous that an accent
would differ on the basis of

00:39:54.120 --> 00:39:55.770
whether a person's
nice or not.

00:39:55.770 --> 00:39:59.320
But this is thought to be the
reason why you see so many

00:39:59.320 --> 00:40:03.860
athletes and movie stars doing
ads because they're asking you

00:40:03.860 --> 00:40:07.740
to leak that same way.

00:40:07.740 --> 00:40:11.210
Oh, if Kobe Bryant uses that
deodorant, that deodorant must

00:40:11.210 --> 00:40:13.450
be awesome.

00:40:13.450 --> 00:40:18.190
So that's why they care that
actors, celebrities, that's

00:40:18.190 --> 00:40:19.990
why they have those ads because
many people have

00:40:19.990 --> 00:40:21.810
positive feelings about them.

00:40:21.810 --> 00:40:23.930
And if they can leak into
actions, they can certainly

00:40:23.930 --> 00:40:27.890
leak into what beer you drink
or what make up you get.

00:40:27.890 --> 00:40:36.370
So now, the problems with
these what we might call

00:40:36.370 --> 00:40:40.110
shortcuts to judging people,
first impressions and that

00:40:40.110 --> 00:40:43.420
kind of stuff, is when we're
making judgements of other

00:40:43.420 --> 00:40:47.210
people is that we do this very
quickly and unconsciously.

00:40:47.210 --> 00:40:50.200
Nobody thinks, if you ask them,
that they go around

00:40:50.200 --> 00:40:53.970
misjudging people by the basis
of very superficial things.

00:40:53.970 --> 00:40:56.250
But 1,000 experiments show
that, on average,

00:40:56.250 --> 00:40:57.760
we tend to do that.

00:40:57.760 --> 00:41:01.770
So these stereotypes
have effects.

00:41:01.770 --> 00:41:03.760
Once we make the decision,
in influences our actual

00:41:03.760 --> 00:41:04.840
behavioral.

00:41:04.840 --> 00:41:08.450
So here's one example where
people tried to show this idea

00:41:08.450 --> 00:41:12.060
that we might have some sort of
negative idea of somebody

00:41:12.060 --> 00:41:14.320
for some reason.

00:41:14.320 --> 00:41:16.640
Now, here's the self-fulfilling
prophecy.

00:41:16.640 --> 00:41:19.110
Because we have a negative
thought about them, we don't

00:41:19.110 --> 00:41:22.060
behave with them as nicely
as we might.

00:41:22.060 --> 00:41:24.460
Now, that person who we haven't
treated nicely, of

00:41:24.460 --> 00:41:26.400
course, is responding to feeling
like they're not

00:41:26.400 --> 00:41:27.400
treated nicely.

00:41:27.400 --> 00:41:29.720
And they go, aha!

00:41:29.720 --> 00:41:30.520
Just what I thought.

00:41:30.520 --> 00:41:32.260
This person stinks.

00:41:32.260 --> 00:41:35.720
And so you have this circle, a
positive or a negative spiral,

00:41:35.720 --> 00:41:38.130
in how you treat somebody, how
they respond to how you treat

00:41:38.130 --> 00:41:40.490
them, and how you think
more about them.

00:41:40.490 --> 00:41:45.180
So an example they did
of this, again using

00:41:45.180 --> 00:41:48.830
attractiveness, the dating
discussion, is they gave in

00:41:48.830 --> 00:41:52.050
this case male participants a
picture that suggested a woman

00:41:52.050 --> 00:41:54.780
they were talking who they did
not see was either more or

00:41:54.780 --> 00:41:56.700
less conventionally
attractive.

00:41:56.700 --> 00:42:00.990
And then, they had a 10 minute
conversation back and forth.

00:42:00.990 --> 00:42:03.720
Then, they brought in some other
males in this study.

00:42:03.720 --> 00:42:05.130
And they asked them to listen.

00:42:05.130 --> 00:42:06.850
They don't know anything
about the experiment.

00:42:06.850 --> 00:42:08.850
They just hear a conversation.

00:42:08.850 --> 00:42:11.280
And they say, listen to this
conversation with this woman.

00:42:11.280 --> 00:42:13.330
Tell us from your impression,
how animated is she?

00:42:13.330 --> 00:42:14.830
How enthusiastic is she?

00:42:14.830 --> 00:42:18.760
How much is she enjoying herself
in this conversation?

00:42:18.760 --> 00:42:19.880
And this will not
surprise you.

00:42:19.880 --> 00:42:21.670
In fact, in some sense
it's almost trivial.

00:42:21.670 --> 00:42:25.030
But in the more attractive
condition-- now, the raters

00:42:25.030 --> 00:42:25.650
don't know that.

00:42:25.650 --> 00:42:26.270
They don't know anything.

00:42:26.270 --> 00:42:28.760
They just hear a discussion
going back and forth.

00:42:28.760 --> 00:42:31.240
The women were more sociable,
poised, humorous,

00:42:31.240 --> 00:42:32.380
and socially adept.

00:42:32.380 --> 00:42:33.750
They were rated that
way by the raters.

00:42:33.750 --> 00:42:35.000
Why?

00:42:37.110 --> 00:42:39.370
Because the men who got the more
attractive pictures were

00:42:39.370 --> 00:42:41.500
being nicer in their
conversational style.

00:42:41.500 --> 00:42:43.610
The women were responding,
having a better conversation

00:42:43.610 --> 00:42:44.490
back and forth.

00:42:44.490 --> 00:42:47.390
And so this is an example of
the cycle between, in this

00:42:47.390 --> 00:42:51.010
case, random and misleading
information and the

00:42:51.010 --> 00:42:52.530
behavior you have.

00:42:52.530 --> 00:42:54.660
And then once you have that
thing, you really start to

00:42:54.660 --> 00:42:55.600
alter the situation.

00:42:55.600 --> 00:42:57.720
That impression changes
how you behave.

00:42:57.720 --> 00:42:59.130
The other person responds
to that behavior.

00:42:59.130 --> 00:43:02.480
And that's a self-fulfilling
style.

00:43:06.140 --> 00:43:08.590
Let me switch for just a couple
minutes to talk about

00:43:08.590 --> 00:43:11.880
this idea we mentioned before
that the vast majority of

00:43:11.880 --> 00:43:14.780
experimental psychology of the
kind I just described to you

00:43:14.780 --> 00:43:17.400
is conducted in what people call
WEIRD societies, Western,

00:43:17.400 --> 00:43:20.240
Educated, Industrial, Rich,
and Democratic.

00:43:20.240 --> 00:43:23.060
There's not a lot of research
in impoverished countries.

00:43:23.060 --> 00:43:23.800
There's no research.

00:43:23.800 --> 00:43:27.730
There's no places to do it
or support to do it.

00:43:27.730 --> 00:43:30.510
So a tremendous amount of
research comes from some

00:43:30.510 --> 00:43:32.730
countries like the
United states,

00:43:32.730 --> 00:43:34.800
Europe, Australia, Japan.

00:43:34.800 --> 00:43:38.010
And in the coming years, more
and more will come of course

00:43:38.010 --> 00:43:41.400
from China and India, South
America and Africa probably

00:43:41.400 --> 00:43:42.790
after that.

00:43:42.790 --> 00:43:46.040
Now, it happens that the
countries that produce a lot

00:43:46.040 --> 00:43:47.950
of the research are the
countries that, when people

00:43:47.950 --> 00:43:52.120
study societal attitudes towards
individuality versus

00:43:52.120 --> 00:43:57.520
fitting in, United States, parts
of Europe, Australia,

00:43:57.520 --> 00:44:00.700
are in the extreme in the
world in emphasizing

00:44:00.700 --> 00:44:01.800
individuality.

00:44:01.800 --> 00:44:04.460
In fact, the United states is
seen as a fantastic outlier

00:44:04.460 --> 00:44:05.940
among other cultures.

00:44:05.940 --> 00:44:07.770
Maybe Canada's close.

00:44:07.770 --> 00:44:11.530
And here's a model that social
psychologists talk about.

00:44:11.530 --> 00:44:13.630
It's a very simple
story in a way.

00:44:13.630 --> 00:44:15.710
And certainly it's averaging
across lots of people.

00:44:15.710 --> 00:44:17.360
So a trouble with cultural
psychology--

00:44:17.360 --> 00:44:19.130
which is where we're at now--

00:44:19.130 --> 00:44:20.120
you can do one or two things.

00:44:20.120 --> 00:44:22.350
You can say culture doesn't
matter, which we think is

00:44:22.350 --> 00:44:23.590
probably unlikely.

00:44:23.590 --> 00:44:26.240
Cultures are huge, the culture
of your home, your community,

00:44:26.240 --> 00:44:27.870
your country, your religion.

00:44:27.870 --> 00:44:30.470
All those things influence
people.

00:44:30.470 --> 00:44:32.260
But then, when you study it,
you tend to reduce it to

00:44:32.260 --> 00:44:34.840
simple things that people
can experimentalize.

00:44:34.840 --> 00:44:36.710
And you tend to, in some
sense, stereotype it.

00:44:36.710 --> 00:44:39.640
But anyway, the idea is that
cultures that emphasize

00:44:39.640 --> 00:44:42.400
individuality say you've
got to be yourself.

00:44:42.400 --> 00:44:44.390
And then, you have some
people around you

00:44:44.390 --> 00:44:46.000
you've got to deal with.

