practically every parent
is worried about

00:55:53.720 --> 00:55:54.490
it for their child.

00:55:54.490 --> 00:55:57.970
It used to be thought of as
a very rare disorder.

00:55:57.970 --> 00:56:03.610
Autism spectrum disorders are
now thought to occur one out

00:56:03.610 --> 00:56:09.440
of every something like
that, approaching 1%.

00:56:09.440 --> 00:56:11.490
Have you seen the ads on TV
about the odds of having

00:56:11.490 --> 00:56:14.370
autism versus the odds
of making the NBA?

00:56:14.370 --> 00:56:16.470
Have any of you seen that?

00:56:16.470 --> 00:56:21.460
Incredibly higher by far to have
autism than to make the

00:56:21.460 --> 00:56:25.070
NBA or many other things
you can think of.

00:56:25.070 --> 00:56:28.060
That's autism awareness efforts
to make people realize

00:56:28.060 --> 00:56:29.970
it's shockingly common.

00:56:29.970 --> 00:56:31.560
Lots of arguments about
why there's

00:56:31.560 --> 00:56:32.490
been a dramatic increase.

00:56:32.490 --> 00:56:34.760
I can tell you that for a while
they thought it was

00:56:34.760 --> 00:56:38.830
awareness only, that people
didn't realize that certain

00:56:38.830 --> 00:56:42.620
children were best understood
as having autism spectrum

00:56:42.620 --> 00:56:45.980
disorders, a range of disorders
that share some

00:56:45.980 --> 00:56:48.870
properties of difficulties
in social cognition,

00:56:48.870 --> 00:56:49.560
communication, and

00:56:49.560 --> 00:56:52.110
stereotyped, repetitive movements.

00:56:52.110 --> 00:56:55.950
But now, most epidemiologic--

00:56:55.950 --> 00:56:57.600
you can't really do
the experiment.

00:56:57.600 --> 00:57:00.300
But most people think there
truly is an increasing number

00:57:00.300 --> 00:57:03.350
for reasons that are not well
understood on top of

00:57:03.350 --> 00:57:04.530
increasing awareness.

00:57:04.530 --> 00:57:07.380
Nowadays, they can diagnose
it by age three.

00:57:07.380 --> 00:57:11.010
A huge mystery is why there's
four boys to every girl with

00:57:11.010 --> 00:57:14.630
autism as far as people have
observed, total mystery.

00:57:14.630 --> 00:57:15.880
Nobody has any idea
why that is.

00:57:21.470 --> 00:57:23.020
So I'm just going to show you
a few things that have been

00:57:23.020 --> 00:57:25.020
found with individuals
with autism.

00:57:25.020 --> 00:57:28.330
So one thing is in terms of the
individual with autism,

00:57:28.330 --> 00:57:32.190
they don't seem to have a
natural desire to socially

00:57:32.190 --> 00:57:34.450
interact with their parents,
their siblings, their

00:57:34.450 --> 00:57:35.270
caretakers.

00:57:35.270 --> 00:57:38.160
It's hard to get them to do
what's easy for most infants,

00:57:38.160 --> 00:57:39.960
which is interact with
people around you.

00:57:39.960 --> 00:57:43.110
That's easy for most infants,
hard for people with autism.

00:57:43.110 --> 00:57:44.910
This is eye tracking.

00:57:44.910 --> 00:57:45.690
When people--

00:57:45.690 --> 00:57:48.020
so this is a path that you
look at when you look at

00:57:48.020 --> 00:57:49.500
somebody else.

00:57:49.500 --> 00:57:52.170
And what's very common as we
look at people is that we

00:57:52.170 --> 00:57:55.880
focus a lot of our attention
to other people's eyes.

00:57:55.880 --> 00:57:57.110
Well, that makes sense.

00:57:57.110 --> 00:57:59.330
You know that from your
everyday experience.

00:57:59.330 --> 00:58:01.070
OK, you look at the mouth and
the ear here and there.

00:58:01.070 --> 00:58:03.080
But it's the eyes of the other
person that seem very

00:58:03.080 --> 00:58:04.760
communicative socially.

00:58:04.760 --> 00:58:07.530
And so you see this triangle
where people go between the

00:58:07.530 --> 00:58:10.010
mouth, the speaking mouth, and
the eyes naturally to figure

00:58:10.010 --> 00:58:11.510
out what's going on
with the person.

00:58:11.510 --> 00:58:13.110
Here's a typical person
with autism.

00:58:13.110 --> 00:58:16.340
You see it's like they don't
even look at this eye, don't

00:58:16.340 --> 00:58:18.960
focus on the eyes, don't
focus on the eyes.

00:58:18.960 --> 00:58:22.910
The original interpretation of
this was a lack of interest in

00:58:22.910 --> 00:58:26.360
looking at these faces
as social targets.

00:58:26.360 --> 00:58:28.640
There's an additional thought
that maybe, for some

00:58:28.640 --> 00:58:30.900
individuals or many with autism,
there's something

00:58:30.900 --> 00:58:34.850
uncomfortable with
dealing with a

00:58:34.850 --> 00:58:37.140
social agent or a person.

00:58:37.140 --> 00:58:39.580
So that's eye tracking.

00:58:39.580 --> 00:58:42.880
And by the way, the same
thing when they were--

00:58:42.880 --> 00:58:44.830
this is spontaneous,
the first picture,

00:58:44.830 --> 00:58:45.590
wherever you want to look.

00:58:45.590 --> 00:58:47.410
Now they said, tell us what
the expression is.

00:58:47.410 --> 00:58:49.010
So you have a task to do.

00:58:49.010 --> 00:58:52.040
And again, pretty much like
before, typically developing

00:58:52.040 --> 00:58:54.820
people focus on the eyes, a
little bit on the mouth.

00:58:54.820 --> 00:58:59.350
And again, you can see these
very wayward locations of

00:58:59.350 --> 00:59:03.450
where individuals with autism
put their glances.

00:59:03.450 --> 00:59:05.710
So you can just imagine a very
different social interaction

00:59:05.710 --> 00:59:08.490
if somebody's looking here or
here at somebody versus the

00:59:08.490 --> 00:59:09.740
person's eyes.

00:59:13.020 --> 00:59:15.340
There's been a fantastic amount
of research about what

00:59:15.340 --> 00:59:17.870
are brain differences in people
with autism spectrum

00:59:17.870 --> 00:59:19.200
disorders and those without.

00:59:19.200 --> 00:59:23.180
There's a fantastic variation
among every disorder, but you

00:59:23.180 --> 00:59:24.730
might say autism even
more, or every

00:59:24.730 --> 00:59:25.950
difference, autism even more.

00:59:25.950 --> 00:59:28.880
It seems like there's just a
fantastic variation among

00:59:28.880 --> 00:59:30.290
people with autism.

00:59:30.290 --> 00:59:33.110
But the one finding that's held
up is this, which is that

00:59:33.110 --> 00:59:35.750
if you measure the total
brain size--

00:59:35.750 --> 00:59:37.950
which is a very gross measure
of the brain--

00:59:37.950 --> 00:59:41.120
that there seems to be early in
development, up until age

00:59:41.120 --> 00:59:44.630
five, an overgrowth of the brain
size in individuals with

00:59:44.630 --> 00:59:47.580
autism that gets back
in development

00:59:47.580 --> 00:59:49.390
to the typical size.

00:59:49.390 --> 00:59:50.930
This is the most replicated.

00:59:50.930 --> 00:59:53.830
Every number here is a different
research study.

00:59:53.830 --> 00:59:56.900
So you can see all of these
up here are clumped here.

00:59:56.900 --> 00:59:58.530
This is the single
most replicable

00:59:58.530 --> 01:00:00.350
finding by far in autism.

01:00:00.350 --> 01:00:03.760
There's an early, apparent
overgrowth of the brain.

01:00:03.760 --> 01:00:06.700
What that means, why that's
associated with difficulties

01:00:06.700 --> 01:00:10.300
in social interaction or
repetitive movements,

01:00:10.300 --> 01:00:12.320
stereotyped interests
is hard to know.

01:00:15.460 --> 01:00:17.340
Early in the course, we
mentioned and we talked about

01:00:17.340 --> 01:00:20.410
theory of mind, understanding
what thoughts

01:00:20.410 --> 01:00:21.410
another person holds.

01:00:21.410 --> 01:00:23.690
And sometimes it's not even
consistent with the physical,

01:00:23.690 --> 01:00:24.830
real world.

01:00:24.830 --> 01:00:30.490
I mentioned to you that it's
severely delayed in autism,

01:00:30.490 --> 01:00:31.770
years later.

01:00:31.770 --> 01:00:33.940
So this is comparing
four-year-olds typically

01:00:33.940 --> 01:00:37.230
developing versus 6 to
12-year-olds with autism.

01:00:37.230 --> 01:00:38.865
And the four-year-olds
outperform the individuals

01:00:38.865 --> 01:00:40.800
with autism on theory
of mind tasks.

01:00:40.800 --> 01:00:46.830
So huge delay in understanding
what the independent mental

01:00:46.830 --> 01:00:48.660
life is like of another
person.

01:00:48.660 --> 01:00:49.337
Yeah?

01:00:49.337 --> 01:00:52.840
AUDIENCE: How do you find, in
general, IQs of people with

01:00:52.840 --> 01:00:54.362
autism compared to--?

01:00:54.362 --> 01:00:57.730
PROFESSOR: So the question
is how are IQs in autism?

01:00:57.730 --> 01:01:00.690
So the answer is you measure--

01:01:00.690 --> 01:01:03.570
so half of individuals with
autism are non-verbal.

01:01:03.570 --> 01:01:06.500
You can't even give
them a test.

01:01:06.500 --> 01:01:08.360
Those are not the ones who
tend to be represented in

01:01:08.360 --> 01:01:12.560
research, behavioral research or
brain research, because you

01:01:12.560 --> 01:01:14.620
can't even ask them
to do things.

01:01:14.620 --> 01:01:18.430
So all the research is skewed
towards the higher functioning

01:01:18.430 --> 01:01:20.610
individuals with autism.

01:01:20.610 --> 01:01:25.210
If you just took their average
IQ, it would be lowish.

01:01:25.210 --> 01:01:29.790
But there's many individuals
with very high IQs also.

01:01:29.790 --> 01:01:32.860
And in fact, what's called
Asperger's syndrome

01:01:32.860 --> 01:01:35.510
specifically refers to
individuals who have the

01:01:35.510 --> 01:01:40.240
social difficulties
characteristic of autism, but

01:01:40.240 --> 01:01:43.510
have a very high functioning
cognitive and IQ level.

01:01:43.510 --> 01:01:46.020
So it runs the whole range.

01:01:46.020 --> 01:01:47.670
If you just took the average,
it'd be low.

01:01:47.670 --> 01:01:51.060
But there's many individuals
who are very high in IQ.

01:01:51.060 --> 01:01:53.580
And so in this study, for
example, they matched IQ by

01:01:53.580 --> 01:01:55.850
having, in this case,
four year olds and

01:01:55.850 --> 01:01:56.516
six to 12 year olds.

01:01:56.516 --> 01:01:58.140
The IQ was even.

01:01:58.140 --> 01:02:00.560
And still, the theory of mind
was much weaker in the

01:02:00.560 --> 01:02:02.010
individuals with autism.

01:02:02.010 --> 01:02:03.590
But it's incredibly
variable, the IQs.

01:02:07.320 --> 01:02:12.060
So here's another way that
people have studied two things

01:02:12.060 --> 01:02:13.810
at once we talk about--

01:02:13.810 --> 01:02:18.790
the human nature to ascribe
social things, social stories

01:02:18.790 --> 01:02:20.470
to things and then how
that plays out

01:02:20.470 --> 01:02:21.590
differently in autism.

01:02:21.590 --> 01:02:24.980
So this is famous work from
Heider and Simmel.

01:02:24.980 --> 01:02:27.970
And you're going to see these
two triangles do something.

01:02:27.970 --> 01:02:30.540
And I want you to figure
out what they're doing.

01:02:33.110 --> 01:02:34.875
What happened there, socially?

01:02:38.214 --> 01:02:40.340
I need somebody to put their
hand up, and the other

01:02:40.340 --> 01:02:41.295
people-- help me out.

01:02:41.295 --> 01:02:42.555
Somebody, put your hand
up and tell me what

01:02:42.555 --> 01:02:44.140
you thought you saw.

01:02:44.140 --> 01:02:45.810
Second last quarter left
of the whole course.

01:02:45.810 --> 01:02:46.970
We gotta have somebody put--

01:02:46.970 --> 01:02:48.110
OK, what do you think you saw?

01:02:48.110 --> 01:02:49.050
AUDIENCE: They were dancing.

01:02:49.050 --> 01:02:49.750
PROFESSOR: They were
kind of dancing.

01:02:49.750 --> 01:02:51.330
Anything else?

01:02:51.330 --> 01:02:52.908
Yeah?

01:02:52.908 --> 01:02:53.886
Go ahead.

01:02:53.886 --> 01:02:56.036
AUDIENCE: That the big one was
trying to get the little one

01:02:56.036 --> 01:02:58.330
to go outside, but the little
one was scared.

01:02:58.330 --> 01:03:01.040
PROFESSOR: Yeah, there's no
right answer, by the way.

01:03:01.040 --> 01:03:04.270
But one I heard, which is
coaxing, that the little one

01:03:04.270 --> 01:03:04.820
was scared.

01:03:04.820 --> 01:03:05.950
They were playing together.

01:03:05.950 --> 01:03:07.880
They're having a nice
relationship.

01:03:07.880 --> 01:03:09.590
Then, the little one doesn't
want to go outside the box.

01:03:09.590 --> 01:03:11.440
Then, the big one has to
coax and support them.

01:03:11.440 --> 01:03:12.910
Were you going to
say that, too?

01:03:12.910 --> 01:03:15.980
Any other thoughts
or feelings?

01:03:15.980 --> 01:03:17.900
So yeah, the most common
interpretation of this-- and

01:03:17.900 --> 01:03:20.120
Heider and Simmel, their
original point was that humans

01:03:20.120 --> 01:03:23.580
want to give social descriptions
to everything.

01:03:23.580 --> 01:03:25.640
Two triangles, what are
you talking about?

01:03:25.640 --> 01:03:28.640
But almost, if we just let our
mind go just a little bit,

01:03:28.640 --> 01:03:30.410
we're almost giving
them animacy.

01:03:30.410 --> 01:03:32.180
They're moving themselves
around.

01:03:32.180 --> 01:03:34.030
They're having social
interactions.

01:03:34.030 --> 01:03:36.300
They have stories where
sometimes there's a bully

01:03:36.300 --> 01:03:38.930
beating up the little, big
circle beating up a little

01:03:38.930 --> 01:03:40.590
circle or dot.

01:03:40.590 --> 01:03:44.140
And we tend to make up these
little stories very easily.

01:03:44.140 --> 01:03:45.445
So the first thing to tell you
is that individuals with

01:03:45.445 --> 01:03:49.330
autism on average, again a big
range on average, don't see

01:03:49.330 --> 01:03:50.920
these stories so much.

01:03:50.920 --> 01:03:55.200
They say on average the two
triangles, what do you mean?

01:03:55.200 --> 01:03:57.950
And you could say that's
not even wrong.

01:03:57.950 --> 01:04:01.590
It's just not the way people
typically interpret things

01:04:01.590 --> 01:04:03.560
that we typically look
for socially.

01:04:03.560 --> 01:04:05.620
And then, you look
in the brain.

01:04:05.620 --> 01:04:06.620
And what happens is this.

01:04:06.620 --> 01:04:09.490
This is brain responses to these
social stories where we

01:04:09.490 --> 01:04:12.090
tend to give it a social
explanation

01:04:12.090 --> 01:04:13.080
versus random displays.

01:04:13.080 --> 01:04:14.650
They can also display where
things whizzing around and

01:04:14.650 --> 01:04:16.680
nobody thinks anything's
happening.

01:04:16.680 --> 01:04:19.230
And what they see is in the
visual cortex, this part of

01:04:19.230 --> 01:04:21.790
the brain that sees the
things, there's equal

01:04:21.790 --> 01:04:24.130
activation in the two groups.

01:04:24.130 --> 01:04:26.420
But in parts of the brain that
we think are involved in

01:04:26.420 --> 01:04:29.740
social interaction, like the
superior temporal sulcus,

01:04:29.740 --> 01:04:32.570
medial prefrontal cortex, areas
from a lot of research

01:04:32.570 --> 01:04:35.770
that we believe is involved in
thinking about other people

01:04:35.770 --> 01:04:38.530
and their feelings and thoughts,
there's very little

01:04:38.530 --> 01:04:41.330
engagement of these areas in
individuals with autism in

01:04:41.330 --> 01:04:42.630
this study.

01:04:42.630 --> 01:04:44.030
So they don't see the
same stories.

01:04:44.030 --> 01:04:47.210
And they don't turn on social
parts of the brain that are

01:04:47.210 --> 01:04:50.800
spontaneously turned on by
typically developing people.

01:04:50.800 --> 01:04:56.420
And here's the last experiment
I'll show you which is this.

01:04:56.420 --> 01:05:00.000
So it turns out our brains
respond and our minds respond

01:05:00.000 --> 01:05:04.355
very strongly to where people
are looking, where their gaze

01:05:04.355 --> 01:05:05.660
is falling.

01:05:05.660 --> 01:05:08.870
So imagine that you're
talking to somebody.

01:05:08.870 --> 01:05:10.370
You're telling them something.

01:05:10.370 --> 01:05:11.410
And their eyes are here.

01:05:11.410 --> 01:05:12.615
Does that bother you?

01:05:12.615 --> 01:05:15.940
OK, yes because we think their
eyes tell us where their

01:05:15.940 --> 01:05:17.300
attention is.

01:05:17.300 --> 01:05:20.190
And if they're not focused on
us, they're not interested.

01:05:20.190 --> 01:05:21.630
And we're offended.

01:05:21.630 --> 01:05:25.750
So here's the experiment now
where they have a computer

01:05:25.750 --> 01:05:26.920
model like this.

01:05:26.920 --> 01:05:29.860
And they throw on suddenly
a display.

01:05:29.860 --> 01:05:31.470
And the person either
looks this way

01:05:31.470 --> 01:05:32.490
or looks the opposite.

01:05:32.490 --> 01:05:35.310
Which would you think is the
natural way a person would

01:05:35.310 --> 01:05:38.210
look naturally if something
interesting

01:05:38.210 --> 01:05:40.220
happened over here?

01:05:40.220 --> 01:05:41.610
They would look towards it.

01:05:41.610 --> 01:05:44.340
It'd be kind of weird to
look away from it.

01:05:44.340 --> 01:05:46.170
And when you look at brain
imaging at what happens in

01:05:46.170 --> 01:05:49.060
those conditions in the superior
temporal sulcus and

01:05:49.060 --> 01:05:51.430
other places, typically
developing people for the

01:05:51.430 --> 01:05:54.200
weird looking away, it's like
a mystery to be solved.

01:05:54.200 --> 01:05:54.730
What's going on?

01:05:54.730 --> 01:05:56.290
Why aren't they looking
at this?

01:05:56.290 --> 01:05:56.750
Are they angry?

01:05:56.750 --> 01:05:58.730
Is there something better
over there?

01:05:58.730 --> 01:05:59.770
it's a social mystery.

01:05:59.770 --> 01:06:01.550
Why is this person
not looking?

01:06:01.550 --> 01:06:03.450
And there's no difference in
those two conditions in the

01:06:03.450 --> 01:06:08.000
study for individuals with
autism as if eyes are looking

01:06:08.000 --> 01:06:10.440
here, eyes are looking there.

01:06:10.440 --> 01:06:11.540
It's just where eyes
are looking.

01:06:11.540 --> 01:06:13.310
What's the difference?

01:06:13.310 --> 01:06:16.640
There's not the spontaneous
social interpretation or

01:06:16.640 --> 01:06:18.660
mystery that needs
to be understood.

01:06:18.660 --> 01:06:20.470
So these are just some of the
differences that people have

01:06:20.470 --> 01:06:23.050
observed looking at the
brains and behavior

01:06:23.050 --> 01:06:24.300
of people with autism.

01:06:24.300 --> 01:06:25.870
Any questions about autism?

01:06:32.310 --> 01:06:32.750
Yeah?

01:06:32.750 --> 01:06:34.121
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:06:34.121 --> 01:06:36.410
in the brain activates
[INAUDIBLE]?

01:06:36.410 --> 01:06:37.170
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:06:37.170 --> 01:06:39.160
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

01:06:39.160 --> 01:06:39.960
PROFESSOR: That's
a good question.

01:06:39.960 --> 01:06:43.330
Do those parts of the brain,
the areas that in typical

01:06:43.330 --> 01:06:45.880
people are turned on for social
cognition, when we

01:06:45.880 --> 01:06:48.070
think about what another
person's thinking or feeling,

01:06:48.070 --> 01:06:49.890
do they ever turn on in
individuals with autism?

01:06:49.890 --> 01:06:51.800
The answer is yes, they do.

01:06:51.800 --> 01:06:52.960
I can tell you that I'm showing
you some of the

01:06:52.960 --> 01:06:55.660
simplest things and probably
roughly correct.

01:06:55.660 --> 01:06:58.080
But there's such a fantastic
variety among people with

01:06:58.080 --> 01:07:00.770
autism and even within
the person.

01:07:00.770 --> 01:07:03.080
Just a very little bit of
different of a condition, all

01:07:03.080 --> 01:07:05.060
of a sudden, some of these
areas will turn on.

01:07:05.060 --> 01:07:07.340
It's been a very big mystery.

01:07:07.340 --> 01:07:08.930
And we don't know whether that's
because we just don't

01:07:08.930 --> 01:07:11.650
understand it right or whether
the variety among patients is

01:07:11.650 --> 01:07:13.990
so great that we're making the
wrong conclusions, saying

01:07:13.990 --> 01:07:15.970
autism is like this.

01:07:15.970 --> 01:07:18.710
And that may be true of 5% of
